      <title>Optative Mood</title>
      <author> szents958 </author>
      <link>https://www.scribblehub.com/series/1804826/optative-mood/</link>
      <comments>https://www.scribblehub.com/read/1804826-optative-mood/chapter/1804831/#comments</comments>
      <guid isPermaLink="false">20dcc9873ca97350eeecab11d996086a17e4cbfb</guid>
      <pubDate>Sat, 23 Aug 2025 00:00:00 +0000</pubDate>
      <description>&lt;div class="wi_fic_desc" property="description"&gt;&lt;p&gt;Aoife is a conscript working for the Terran Accord on cracking the language of a mysterious new alien threat. It hasn't been going well, and after nearly three years of failed attempts at translating, Aoife's future is looking bleak. However, a shuttle headed for the planet's surface has some news that will upend her life and her understanding of her place in the universe, courtesy of some very tall plant people.&lt;/p&gt; &lt;/div&gt;&lt;hr&gt;&lt;h3&gt;&lt;a href="https://www.scribblehub.com/read/1804826-optative-mood/chapter/1804831/"&gt;&lt;div class="chapter-title"&gt;A Day in the Life&lt;/div&gt;&lt;/a&gt;&lt;/h3&gt;&lt;div class="chp_raw" id="chp_raw"&gt;&lt;div class="wi_news"&gt; &lt;div class="wi_news_title"&gt;&lt;i class="fa fa-exclamation-triangle" aria-hidden="true" style="padding-right:5px;"&gt;&lt;/i&gt; Announcement&lt;/div&gt; &lt;div class="wi_news_body"&gt;Many thanks to Kanagen and her work No Gods, No Masters for giving me hope for this setting and the desire to actually write something for it.&lt;/p&gt; &lt;p&gt;CW for this chapter: &lt;/p&gt; &lt;div class="sp-wrap sp-wrap-default"&gt; &lt;div class="sp-head" title="Expand"&gt; Spoiler &lt;/div&gt; &lt;div class="sp-body folded"&gt; &lt;p&gt;Intentional deadnaming, misgendering, the general cruelty of a fascist society&lt;/p&gt; &lt;div class="spdiv"&gt;[collapse]&lt;/div&gt; &lt;/div&gt; &lt;/div&gt;&lt;/div&gt; &lt;/div&gt; &lt;p&gt;&lt;strong&gt;Chapter 1 - A Day in the Life&lt;/strong&gt;&lt;/p&gt; &lt;p&gt;The blaring of her alarm, set far too early for her liking, pulled Aoife to the edge of consciousness. She grumbled and remained within the relative warmth of her bed, though her sheets were thin enough that they didn't provide much comfort. She rolled over and shut off the alarm just before it would have sent an alert to a supervisor, slowly rising out of bed and walking over to the closet to pick which variety of beige coveralls she wanted to wear today. The Terran Accord didn't much value individuality in their government workers, especially from those who had been conscripted to aid in the war effort. Clothes on, she grabbed the synthcube that had been dispensed next to the closet and swallowed it with a minimum of chewing. She surreptitiously grabbed the bottle of pills she had managed to bring in with her and placed one under her tongue before heading to the door of her small room and setting out for the day.&lt;/p&gt; &lt;p&gt;The halls were slowly filling with others in similar circumstances to her own. Those who had useful skills to the Accord but had not readily volunteered for service when the government announced a new xeno threat on the edge of Accord space had found themselves awoken in the night by bands of soldiers with "conscription orders" and taken to a facility like this one. It was soul-draining in the way that most Accord buildings were, designed to maximize productivity at a minimum of expense. The lights were a bit too bright in the halls and the hum of ventilation just a bit too loud so as to discourage loitering, and there were no places to sit outside of the main building's workstations. These dormitories were directly connected to the main building, so conscripts didn't need to go outside at any point during their day, funneled from work to sleep to work again. All those living here had taken on a decidedly wan complexion as a result, though Aoife's skin had needed little persuasion to get to that point, already fairly pale from a lack of outdoor activity.&lt;/p&gt; &lt;p&gt;As they shuffled into the main building of the facility, another conscript fell into step beside her, giving her a light nudge to alert her to his presence. "Morning A," he said, grinning, "Any amazing plans over in the land of not knowing what the hell the xenos are saying to each other today?"&lt;/p&gt; &lt;p&gt;She sighed and forced a thin smile. "Morning Jamie," she replied, "Unless said xenos decide to send us something unencrypted or otherwise legible, it seems like I'll have to be content with doing my best Sisyphus impression."&lt;/p&gt; &lt;p&gt;A crease appeared between Jamie's brows. "I'm going to assume that's a very clever language reference or something and laugh along. Ha ha ha," his forced laughter was cut by a genuine smile, "But I hope you have some kind of breakthrough soon. I heard the higher-ups are talking about downsizing, and underperforming groups are probably going to get the axe."&lt;/p&gt; &lt;p&gt;Aoife waved dismissively, "Nah, the one benefit of a sudden war with an unknown enemy is that all your intelligence agencies need information from enemy channels. Maybe one of these days we'll actually have something to show them and get them off our back for a day or two, until they find some new language puzzle for us to decipher."&lt;/p&gt; &lt;p&gt;"That's the spirit! Make sure you keep that optimism up when you actually see whatever gibberish they give you today," Jamie laughed, giving her another good-natured nudge, "Well, they probably won't let us lollygag around here too much longer. Let's get to work, lest we displease our all-seeing overlords."&lt;/p&gt; &lt;p&gt;She and Jamie parted ways, with him taking a left at a fork in the hallway to head towards the department of Data Interpretation. He was apparently some kind of savant when it came to recognizing and interpreting patterns, but the Accord had him doing basic data entry and organization. Aoife figured if he were of a mind to, he probably could have been running strategy meetings, and with more success than whatever bigwig's son they had doing it now. Instead, the war was dragging on, though locked away as they were, none of the conscripts had any idea how the Accord was faring beyond the mercurial moods of their supervisors.&lt;/p&gt; &lt;p&gt;The right fork took Aoife to the Department of Xenolinguistics, a large room with desks lined end to end below a raised platform for presentations or general supervision of the workers. Every linguist of any talent or skill in the region had ended up here, whether voluntarily or otherwise, and given the rate of progress they'd been making, Aoife suspected that they'd also started grabbing the linguists who lacked talent or skill. She began walking toward her workspace but found a tall figure standing in her way.&lt;/p&gt; &lt;p&gt;Her direct supervisor, Mr. Sala, stood between her and her chair, a deeply unpleasant smile on his face as he fiddled with his shirtsleeve. Where most of the population of this facility bore the beige jumpsuit and barely-fed-enough physique of those that had been conscripted to the war effort, Mr. Sala bore a bronzed tan and a suit that screamed of trying too hard to look wealthy. His sneer deepened as Aoife approached. "Good morning, Jack," he said, his tone as insincere as he could manage, "I hope you're ready to put up some results this morning. The minds in charge of the war effort are getting impatient with your lack of progress."&lt;/p&gt; &lt;p&gt;"That's still not my name," she muttered, avoiding eye contact and trying to slide past to her desk, "and maybe I'd be able to put up some results if the cryptographers gave us something intelligible, or if we were allowed anything about the xenos we are supposed to translating the language of."&lt;/p&gt; &lt;p&gt;Sala leaned in uncomfortably close, forcing Aoife to back away a step. "What was that? Some new kernel of wisdom to enlighten us with, Mr. Clark? Maybe the breakthrough we've been waiting for?"&lt;/p&gt; &lt;p&gt;Aoife schooled her expression to avoid showing the disgust she felt as he got close to her. "Nothing, sir," she said, "Just what I've mentioned before about language being a function of culture. Without knowing anything about these xenos or what their culture is like, we're working blindfolded and with one hand tied behind our back. Perhaps with some information about the enemy-"&lt;/p&gt; &lt;p&gt;"That information is on a strict need-to-know basis," Mr. Sala cut her off, his expression darkening, "And you can be sure that you do not need to know. The information you've been given is the result of our best cryptographers working tirelessly to decode messages intercepted from the enemy fleet by our most advanced technology. This team is the weak link in the chain that leads to us unlocking all of the enemy's innermost secrets, and you, Jack, are the weak link among weak links. You don't want to be convicted of treason, I'm sure, but someone who had to be conscripted to the war effort and didn't produce &lt;em&gt;any&lt;/em&gt; meaningful results during his time? I'm sure you can put the pieces together."&lt;/p&gt; &lt;p&gt;His threat delivered, Mr. Sala ambled off, once again plastering a congenial smile on his face as he walked towards the raised platform at the front of the room. "Good talk, Jack!" he called over his shoulder, as Aoife finally took her seat and got herself ready for the day to come.&lt;/p&gt; &lt;hr /&gt; &lt;p&gt;Aoife sighed as she leaned back in her chair, ignoring the way the hard edges of its back dug into her ribs. Not only were the latest offerings from the cryptographers still entirely untranslatable, it was like whoever was sending the messages was trying to make as little sense as possible. There was no semblance of a pattern that she could try and apply a grammatical structure to, and it seemed like no two words were used twice in any given message. Even when she cross-referenced with multiple transmissions, it was like a different language was being used in each transmission, or else each speaker's vocabulary was so hyperspecific that there was almost no overlap. Her repeated requests for information about the suspected context of the messages or even a tidbit about the culture of the xenos had been met first with denials and then without a response at all. As a result, she had no clue what sort of words she should even be looking for when trying to translate. It felt like trying to find a needle in a haystack, if the haystack covered the entire surface of the planet. She couldn't even if this language shared any features with any of the languages she knew - as far as she could tell, it didn't even have basic linguistic features like common distribution of vocabulary that she could use to start narrowing down meanings. But the people at the top were expecting results, and Mr. Sala had made it clear that her freedom specifically was on the line if they failed. So she had to get something out of this, no matter what. She wracked her brain as she hunched back over the latest transmission to cross her desk.Maybe looking for signs of tone indicators again? If she could prove it was necessary to listen to the original transmissions she might actually be able to make some progress.&lt;/p&gt; &lt;p&gt;The texts continued to prove as impenetrable as ever, resisting any attempt to group them in a way that even proved these translations were anything more than meaningless gibberish. Maybe it was some kind of individualized idiolect that required you to know the person sending the message? That would be a fundamentally unbreakable code but pretty useless at scale unless the xenos were some kind of massive collective consciousness that let everyone know everyone else on a personal level. Were they a collective consciousness? Without some kind of contextual information, she had no way to know. Hours slipped by as she worked. A synthcube appeared from a dispenser at her desk around six hours after she started working and was quickly downed without much thought.&lt;/p&gt; &lt;p&gt;Something changed around hour seven or eight of work. A new transmission was sent to the data pad she worked off of, this one marked high priority. That only served to frustrate Aoife, though, because how did anyone know that this particular message was high priority if nobody had any clue what it said? Then another high priority message came. Then another. Every new transmission being sent to her was now being marked high priority, which didn't help her in translating the texts, but did give her some new information to sift through all the same. Something clearly had the brass riled up, and they were either panicking or furious. Knowing how Accord leadership operated, likely it was both at once. The only question was what could possibly have happened to get them acting this way, dropping the absurdly tight information security they'd held to this entire time in the name of… what? What kind of information were they hoping these messages contained, exactly?&lt;/p&gt; &lt;p&gt;There were, however, no answers forthcoming to that particular mystery, and so the constant barrage of high priority messages began to fade into the background, quickly becoming the new normal for Aoife as she continued to bang her head against the wall that was the xeno language. The messages were, of course, not noticeably different in content from before the change in labelling, though it did seem as though they were increasing in frequency. The larger data set should have been helpful, should have let her narrow down common words and phrases that she could use to begin the effort of deciphering the language, but the words remained frustratingly resistant to being grouped or categorized. The initial excitement of a change from the monotony of her daily work could not hold out under the frustration and boredom, and she soon found herself leaning back once more, her eyes searching for anything of visual interest to distract her a moment from her apparently impossible task.&lt;/p&gt; &lt;p&gt;Sala walked past her desk and Aoife tensed up, certain she was about to get chewed out for "slacking on the job," but he walked past with hardly a glance in her direction, making his way out into the hall and leaving them unsupervised for the first time Aoife could recall. Immediately a low chatter began amongst the collected workers, and Aoife's neighbor turned to her. "So what do you think is up with all the high priority transmissions?" she asked, "I figure the Accord must have the xenos on the run and they're trying to keep them from scurrying back into whatever hole they crawled out of. Can't think of what else would get all the bosses so excited."&lt;/p&gt; &lt;p&gt;"Maybe…" she replied. Aoife didn't think that Sala had looked particularly excited as he left the room, and in fact looked rather vexed. Besides, excitement for Sala usually resulted in increased harassment for her, much like what had happened this morning.&lt;/p&gt; &lt;p&gt;Her neighbor continued chattering excitedly as she thought, "I've gotta say though, it's a good thing if the Accord is finally ending the war because we have been making &lt;em&gt;no&lt;/em&gt; progress here on these transmissions. I swear sometimes I think the xenos aren't actually capable of language and we've just been intercepting random noise from their fleet. Ha! Maybe that's why we beat them, if they don't even know how to talk to each other."&lt;/p&gt; &lt;p&gt;Aoife didn't think that seemed particularly likely either. Any spacefaring race would need some kind of communcation amongst themselves if for no other reason than the logistics of long-range supply and fleet directing. She kept silent, though, and let her neighbor continue talking while she thought. The fact that they were even able to have conversations during the workday at all indicated that things were going either extremely well or extremely poorly. Whether that was on a large scale or a local one, it was hard to say. Maybe the upper management of this facility were being reprimanded or transferred for failure to produce results, or maybe Sala was getting a promotion for keeping all the lazy linguists in line and he'd rushed out to move into his new office. That latter option struck her as particularly unlikely - Sala was many things, but an effective manager was not one of them - but the Terran Accord was seldom known for promoting based on ability.&lt;/p&gt; &lt;p&gt;Her thoughts were cut short as the door opened once more and Sala walked back through the door. Everybody fell silent, but Sala could clearly tell what had been happening. "Do you all think you're clever, slacking off on the job like this? This department is not putting up anywhere near the numbers it needs to for you to think you have the privilege of chatting to each other. Get back to work!" He stalked up towards the manager's platform. "Clark!" he called, "Get up here, now."&lt;/p&gt; &lt;p&gt;Aoife's stomach dropped as she slowly made her way towards the platform. She had no idea why Sala would want to talk to her, but there was no way it was anything good, given everything else that had been happening. Sala wasn't smiling, and was pacing around the platform, rounding on her immediately when she topped the last step. "I hope you have something meaningful to report, Jack," he snarled, "Any progress in your translations?"&lt;/p&gt; &lt;p&gt;"Well… " Aoife shuffled uncomfortable as Sala stared her down, "I have been toying with the theory that the xeno language might be a series of individual idiolects that are only translatable if the receiver knows the sender. It would make sense if the xenos have a hive mind or some kind of collective consciousness and-"&lt;/p&gt; &lt;p&gt;"So not only do you not have anything," he interrupted, "but you are now offering excuses for why it can't be done. I shouldn't have expected more from someone like you, and yet I still find myself disappointed. There will be consequences for this, I can promise you that. Nobody here is getting out of this unscathed, and especially not you, Jack."&lt;/p&gt; &lt;p&gt;As she was about to object to him calling her &lt;em&gt;that&lt;/em&gt; again, Sala suddenly turned to the rest of the room. "Alright everyone!" he called, "Work's over for the day, go back to your quarters and await further direction. Chop chop!" He turned back to Aoife. "I'll have something &lt;em&gt;special &lt;/em&gt;planned for you before I see you next, and you can count on that. Get out of here."&lt;/p&gt; &lt;p&gt;She didn't need to be told twice to get out of Sala's presence, and she hurried down the steps and joined the crowd heading toward the door. It was immediately apparent that they weren't the only ones who had been dismissed, as the halls were filled with people slowly shuffling towards the workers' quarters. She kept her eye out for Jamie as she walked, but wasn't able to see him. It was a shame, he might have had some sort of inkling what was going on, or at least could likely have put together the pieces better than she had so far, but she would had to be satisfied with what she'd deduced by herself and hope that tomorrow would bring some more clues. She found her door relatively quickly and entered if for no other reason than to get out of the unpleasant hallway and away from the crowd of people. The workers' quarters were not designed with leisure in mind, though, and with nothing else to do in the bare room, Aoife settled herself down to try and get some sleep.&lt;/p&gt; &lt;hr /&gt; &lt;p&gt;She was pulled from her sleep some time later by a blaring alarm, though this one was coming from some loudspeaker hidden in the walls rather than the built-in alarm clock. "ALL PERSONNEL REPORT IMMEDIATELY TO THE FRONT OF THE BUILDING FOR INSTRUCTION. DELAYS WILL NOT BE TOLERATED. ALL PERSONNEL REPORT IMMEDIATELY TO THE FRONT OF THE BUILDING FOR INSTRUCTION."&lt;/p&gt; &lt;p&gt;The message and alarm continued to repeat, so Aoife got out of bed and made her way to the door, having slept in her jumpsuit. She was clearly not the only one who had been pulled from sleep, as other similarly rumpled people were making their way through the hallway towards the front of the facility. The mass of confused people only increased as more and more quarters were emptied and funneled towards the front of the building. Aoife thought there ought not to be enough space for everyone in the facility to gather in the front foyer, but it was quickly made clear why that wasn't an issue as she saw workers being directed out the front doors. She was swept along with the crowd until she herself was ushered out the front door.&lt;/p&gt; &lt;p&gt;The light of Oberon's star, dim though it was, was blinding to her after who knew how long inside the building. Casting her gaze downward and squinting, she was moved along further than she expected before she found herself gazing at a familiar pair of nouveau riche loafers. Her eyes having adjusted somewhat to the light, she looked up at Sala and was met with two deeply concerning sights. The first was Sala glaring at her and holding out a rifle towards her, looking impatient. The second was looming behind him, far larger than she thought it probably needed to be. Sitting in front of the Terran Accord Regional Command Center was a decidedly alien-looking shuttle, and lined up opposite it were dozens of conscripted workers holding rifles.&lt;/p&gt; &lt;div class="wi_authornotes"&gt; &lt;div&gt; &lt;div class="p-avatar-wrap"&gt;&lt;a class="avatar has-link" href="/profile/123322/szents958/"&gt;&lt;img id="acc_ava_change profile" alt="" src="https://cdn.scribblehub.com/avatar/s/30/ava_123322_1755380184.jpg"&gt;&lt;/a&gt;&lt;/div&gt; &lt;p&gt;&lt;span class="an_username"&gt;&lt;a href="/profile/123322/szents958/"&gt;szents958&lt;/a&gt;&lt;/span&gt;&lt;/div&gt; &lt;div style="clear: both;"&gt;&lt;/div&gt; &lt;div class="wi_authornotes_body"&gt;  And so begins what is, if I include everything I have written so far, the longest individual work I've ever written. And I'm only three chapters in on my end. I'm going to try and keep writing at a decent pace to get this thing out of my brain, maybe a chapter per week, with a buffer between me writing and posting as insurance. Next time: Aoife's Terrible, Horrible, No Good, Very Bad Day&lt;/div&gt; &lt;/p&gt;&lt;/div&gt;&lt;/p&gt; &lt;/div&gt;</description>
