    <item>
      <title>The Coven&amp;#8217;s Contractor</title>
      <author> Mooseebae </author>
      <link>https://www.scribblehub.com/series/1802045/the-covens-contractor/</link>
      <comments>https://www.scribblehub.com/read/1802045-the-covens-contractor/chapter/1802150/#comments</comments>
      <guid isPermaLink="false">7eb465eff7b7345786f3d2891971a2065173e4ad</guid>
      <pubDate>Thu, 21 Aug 2025 00:00:00 +0000</pubDate>
      <description>&lt;div class="wi_fic_desc" property="description"&gt;&lt;p&gt;Author's note before reading: Read at your own risk, this probably won't go anywhere because I have commitment issues with stories and only write when I feel inspired every couple months, so don't expect a proper continuation. I should probably take ADHD meds if I'm being honest.&lt;/p&gt; &lt;p&gt;Synopsis: A young man gets kidnapped by a coven of witches as a sacrifice in a demon summoning ritual. Things don't go according to their plan, and instead of summoning the archdemoness of regal blood, they inadvertently turn the man into her progeny. Now reborn as Sanguinaria's daughter, she must bend the contract with the coven to her advantage, win the favor of her 'mother' and accept her new life as a demoness.&lt;/p&gt; &lt;/div&gt;&lt;hr&gt;&lt;h3&gt;&lt;a href="https://www.scribblehub.com/read/1802045-the-covens-contractor/chapter/1802150/"&gt;&lt;div class="chapter-title"&gt;Chapter 1&lt;/div&gt;&lt;/a&gt;&lt;/h3&gt;&lt;div class="chp_raw" id="chp_raw"&gt;&lt;p&gt;&lt;span style="font-weight:400"&gt;Misted-over lights and the glowing business-front signs of restaurants and shops lined the sides of the dark foggy street. A blanket of quiet and gentle wind was my only company. Mom had offered me a drive home from work, but I was too tired to deal with her scorn.&lt;/span&gt;&lt;/p&gt; &lt;p&gt;&lt;span style="font-weight:400"&gt;My stomach growled in complaint as I walked, so I reached into the fast food bag and ate a handful of fries.&lt;/span&gt;&lt;/p&gt; &lt;p&gt;&lt;span style="font-weight:400"&gt;“Why can’t it always be night?” I mumbled while chewing. There was something unsettling to me about the city during the day. The gazes of others forced me to slouch, to graze the pavement with my eyes instead of the world ahead, made worse when I was illuminated by the sun. Nobody directly judged me, I knew, but something about a stranger's eyes lingering on me made me feel judged nonetheless; a distinct feeling of wrongness made itself known in my core, like what they were seeing was wrong, or less than human.&lt;/span&gt;&lt;/p&gt; &lt;p&gt;&lt;span style="font-weight:400"&gt;I’m in my twenties now, every friend I once knew has seemingly surpassed me, my mother makes that much known on a daily basis. For the life of me though, I can’t figure out what to do no matter how much I wish I could. A very human and nasty instinct to escape instead of confront has ruled my life ever since graduating from high school. I tried to just pick something at random and stick with it, but I couldn’t bring myself to do that either. At least then I’d have a better answer when asked about what I was up to.&lt;/span&gt;&lt;/p&gt; &lt;p&gt;&lt;span style="font-weight:400"&gt;Recently things have only gotten worse. My dead-end job couldn’t keep up with the bills, and so I’m once again living under the roof of my well-wishing parents. I let out a drawn sigh as I continued to walk towards their house.&lt;/span&gt;&lt;/p&gt; &lt;p&gt;&lt;span style="font-weight:400"&gt;A text interrupted my line of thought.&lt;/span&gt;&lt;/p&gt; &lt;p&gt;&lt;span style="font-weight:400"&gt;23:34 Mom: u better not b wasting ur money on that slop again&lt;/span&gt;&lt;span style="font-weight:400"&gt;&lt;br /&gt;&lt;/span&gt;&lt;span style="font-weight:400"&gt; 23:35 Mom: theres leftovers in the fridge&lt;/span&gt;&lt;span style="font-weight:400"&gt;&lt;br /&gt;&lt;/span&gt;&lt;span style="font-weight:400"&gt; 23:35 Mom: b quiet when u get home, harley is sleeping and works early&lt;/span&gt;&lt;/p&gt; &lt;p&gt;&lt;span style="font-weight:400"&gt;I rolled my eyes. If I was going to have to be shamed for not doing more with my life, I wished she could at the very least stop pestering me over minor shit like this. The only point I could agree with her on was that I should be saving money to run the hell away again. Living with them was its own kind of hell, with nowhere to escape their expectations when I can’t just ignore their texts or calls.&lt;/span&gt;&lt;/p&gt; &lt;p&gt;&lt;span style="font-weight:400"&gt;A van pulled over across the street ahead of me, the first car I’d seen in the last twenty minutes of walking. I felt the hairs on the back of my neck prickle, and a chill ran down my spine. Why couldn’t they just keep on their way? Why did the only people I’d seen all night stop there? I couldn’t tell if there was something unnerving about the situation, so much as the dread of having to be ‘witnessed’ by anyone at all.&lt;/span&gt;&lt;/p&gt; &lt;p&gt;&lt;span style="font-weight:400"&gt;It wasn’t bad enough that they parked near me. The van door slid open behind me, and I could hear footsteps echo between the buildings. My heart beat creeped up at the distinct possibility that they could be following me; I ignored those thoughts and forced myself to breathe. Most people would go into fight or flight if they felt something was deeply wrong nearby, but not me. My motto could be boiled down to: &lt;/span&gt;&lt;i&gt;&lt;span style="font-weight:400"&gt;If I pretend nothing is wrong, then nothing is wrong.&lt;/span&gt;&lt;/i&gt;&lt;span style="font-weight:400"&gt; As much as that attitude would help me to ignore the more abstract problems I face day-to-day, it certainly wouldn’t stop human traffickers, or muggers.&lt;/span&gt;&lt;/p&gt; &lt;p&gt;&lt;span style="font-weight:400"&gt;The footsteps grew louder as they gained on me, so logically, I pulled out my phone and tried to look busy, scrolling through various chat histories, sending some nonsense to my friends about a new game coming out; anything but acknowledge that whoever was behind me had just followed me around the corner and off the main road.&lt;/span&gt;&lt;/p&gt; &lt;p&gt;&lt;span style="font-weight:400"&gt;It was stupid, I realized, if whoever these people were, were about to do some illegal shit to me, I’d just brought them to an area that guaranteed no witnesses. Of course, that was only IF they were going to do something to me, my perceived logic led only to more denial justifying my currently rightful fear as the usual social anxiety I was more used to facing in the daylight.&lt;/span&gt;&lt;/p&gt; &lt;p&gt;&lt;span style="font-weight:400"&gt;Right now the only things I could think about were how sweaty I was, how much I wished I was alone, how I wished I could just disappear from everyone's view and be invisible. Even if whoever was behind me didn’t harm me, they might say something to me, then they’d realize what a mess I was, how much I stunk of BO; they’d somehow bore a hole in my flesh with their eyes and see me as disgusting as I felt in my own skin.&lt;/span&gt;&lt;/p&gt; &lt;p&gt;&lt;span style="font-weight:400"&gt;I was almost grateful when they wrapped an arm around me and pressed a damp cloth to my mouth. Almost. At least for once my suspicion of people wasn’t unfounded.&lt;/span&gt;&lt;/p&gt; &lt;p&gt;&lt;span style="font-weight:400"&gt;“Well, that was easy,” the henchman who grabbed me commented with a chuckle.&lt;/span&gt;&lt;/p&gt; &lt;p&gt;&lt;span style="font-weight:400"&gt; The other shrugged. “From what Lady Burke says, He's barely alive to begin with. Practically a ghost.”&lt;/span&gt;&lt;/p&gt; &lt;p&gt;&lt;span style="font-weight:400"&gt;The van pulled up next to them and they tossed me in without much fanfare.&lt;/span&gt;&lt;/p&gt; &lt;hr /&gt; &lt;p&gt; &lt;/p&gt; &lt;p&gt;&lt;span style="font-weight:400"&gt;As I slowly gained consciousness, I heard a conversation between two women nearby.&lt;/span&gt;&lt;/p&gt; &lt;p&gt;&lt;span style="font-weight:400"&gt;A young, but husky woman spoke. “Mistress Hayes! There should be no need to waste so many resources on extraction when there’s so little there. I get that it is important for the vessel to have space, but this specimen has such a pitifully small soul, it shouldn’t matter!”&lt;/span&gt;&lt;/p&gt; &lt;p&gt;&lt;span style="font-weight:400"&gt;An older woman whose authority carried through her voice with an unnatural quality replied, “Do not forget your place Charlotte! I have to concede you have a point on saving precious ritual components would make it worth it. However, this is unprecedented in our coven’s history, so we will have to tread with caution, never underestimate the unknown when it comes to our field.”&lt;/span&gt;&lt;/p&gt; &lt;p&gt;&lt;span style="font-weight:400"&gt;I blearily opened my eyes, confirming what I suspected: I’d been kidnapped. A circular room of old gray brick surrounded me, lit by dozens of dim candles. I was too restrained to be able to see the women talking, so I kept quiet, not wanting to alert them that I was awake.&lt;/span&gt;&lt;/p&gt; &lt;p&gt;&lt;i&gt;&lt;span style="font-weight:400"&gt;Is this how it’s gonna end? Tied up in some old hag’s basement?&lt;/span&gt;&lt;/i&gt;&lt;/p&gt; &lt;p&gt;&lt;span style="font-weight:400"&gt;I hoped they weren’t going to kill me, but from what I was overhearing they seemed to be some kind of cult, which didn’t help my nerves.&lt;/span&gt;&lt;/p&gt; &lt;p&gt;&lt;span style="font-weight:400"&gt;“We’ll go ahead with the ritual, but we will need safeties in place. Go summon your sisters, and have them help prepare demonic restraining and banishing wards in case it tries anything. I feel silly asking, but you weren’t seen retrieving the vessel, right?” The older-sounding woman conceded.&lt;/span&gt;&lt;/p&gt; &lt;p&gt;&lt;span style="font-weight:400"&gt;“Yes, Mistress Hayes, I made sure to use perception wards when retrieving it. I will summon my sisters at once.” The younger one — my kidnapper — assured. Quickly after speaking, I heard a pair of footsteps grow further away into nothing.&lt;/span&gt;&lt;/p&gt; &lt;p&gt;&lt;span style="font-weight:400"&gt;Presumably ‘Mistress Hayes’ let out a heavy sigh before footsteps came closer to me in the center of the room. A moment passed before I felt a flick on my forehead.&lt;/span&gt;&lt;/p&gt; &lt;p&gt;&lt;span style="font-weight:400"&gt;“I know you’re awake, boy.”&lt;/span&gt;&lt;/p&gt; &lt;p&gt;&lt;span style="font-weight:400"&gt;My eyes shot open, revealing the intimidating woman. Rather unlike what I’d expect from a cult leader, she looked like any old grandma. Despite her unsuspecting appearance, she had a dark aura about her.&lt;/span&gt;&lt;/p&gt; &lt;p&gt;&lt;span style="font-weight:400"&gt;Before I could reply, she spoke again. “I don’t care if you eavesdrop, boy. There’s nothing you can do about it anyway. Pretty soon you’ll be nothing but a host for something far greater than you could imagine.” She gave me a taunting smirk and a pat on the shoulder.&lt;/span&gt;&lt;/p&gt; &lt;p&gt;&lt;span style="font-weight:400"&gt;I didn’t believe in this religious hocus-pocus, but every word she said carried a chill that seeped through my bones. It was undeniable that I was afraid; even if they didn’t kill me, whatever she intended to do with me sounded far worse.&lt;/span&gt;&lt;/p&gt; &lt;p&gt;&lt;span style="font-weight:400"&gt;I wouldn’t have to wait long. A dozen women wearing dark robes walked into the room and began drawing weird magical circles in a reddish-brown paint that shimmered in the candlelight.&lt;/span&gt;&lt;/p&gt; &lt;p&gt;&lt;span style="font-weight:400"&gt;Mistress Hayes barked orders at her coven. “Add restraining glyphs at the points of the summoning circle.” Worryingly, that prompted a few of them to break off, surrounding me, doing something on the floor nearby.&lt;/span&gt;&lt;/p&gt; &lt;p&gt;&lt;span style="font-weight:400"&gt;Mistress Hayes took something from one of the nearby cloaked women, an incense burner. She swung it around near my head, wafting the smoke towards me as she circled me. For a cult, they were very organized; the room was silent apart from the robed women painting on the floor and walls, and my occasional whimpering.&lt;/span&gt;&lt;/p&gt; &lt;p&gt;&lt;span style="font-weight:400"&gt;I felt I deserved this in some way. I’d always felt like a burden to those around me, so this felt like karma. I didn’t beg for my life; it was pointless. They’d already kidnapped me. There was no way they’d let me go and expose them.&lt;/span&gt;&lt;/p&gt; &lt;p&gt;&lt;span style="font-weight:400"&gt;Most of the robed women had finished what they were doing, but one of them walked up to me with her paint and held my head up by my hair, pulling my bangs back and revealing my forehead. I flinched and glared at her.&lt;/span&gt;&lt;/p&gt; &lt;p&gt;&lt;span style="font-weight:400"&gt;“What are you doing?” I demanded.&lt;/span&gt;&lt;/p&gt; &lt;p&gt;&lt;span style="font-weight:400"&gt;She sighed but entertained my question. “I’m drawing a target on you so the demon knows who the vessel is.”&lt;/span&gt;&lt;/p&gt; &lt;p&gt;&lt;span style="font-weight:400"&gt;The ‘paint’ was more watery than I thought paint should be, so I followed up. “What are you using to draw on me?”&lt;/span&gt;&lt;/p&gt; &lt;p&gt;&lt;span style="font-weight:400"&gt;“Lamb’s blood.”&lt;/span&gt;&lt;/p&gt; &lt;p&gt;&lt;span style="font-weight:400"&gt;Well, at least it wasn’t human blood, as I had feared. Moments later, she withdrew from me, leaving a slight lonely feeling behind. From the few words we exchanged, she seemed nice enough, and I hadn’t felt the touch of another person in years.&lt;/span&gt;&lt;/p&gt; &lt;p&gt;&lt;span style="font-weight:400"&gt;The cultists, having finished their work, all gathered along the outskirts of the room. Only Mistress Hayes remained near the center, shouting a chant. I watched helplessly, enraptured by the enchanted words:&lt;/span&gt;&lt;/p&gt; &lt;p&gt;&lt;em&gt;&lt;span style="font-weight:400"&gt;“O Sanguinaria, Regina Cruoris,&lt;/span&gt;&lt;span style="font-weight:400"&gt;&lt;br /&gt;&lt;/span&gt;&lt;span style="font-weight:400"&gt; Lady of crimson lineage, Matron of oaths,&lt;/span&gt;&lt;span style="font-weight:400"&gt;&lt;br /&gt;&lt;/span&gt;&lt;span style="font-weight:400"&gt; We open the gate, we inscribe the seal,&lt;/span&gt;&lt;span style="font-weight:400"&gt;&lt;br /&gt;&lt;/span&gt;&lt;span style="font-weight:400"&gt; We bare the vessel, hollow and waiting.”&lt;/span&gt;&lt;/em&gt;&lt;/p&gt; &lt;p&gt;&lt;span style="font-weight:400"&gt;The blood markings all over the ground and on my forehead began to glow.&lt;/span&gt;&lt;/p&gt; &lt;p&gt;&lt;em&gt;&lt;span style="font-weight:400"&gt;“By blood we call thee, by lineage we bind thee,&lt;/span&gt;&lt;span style="font-weight:400"&gt;&lt;br /&gt;&lt;/span&gt;&lt;span style="font-weight:400"&gt; Come forth from the river of scarlet crowns.&lt;/span&gt;&lt;span style="font-weight:400"&gt;&lt;br /&gt;&lt;/span&gt;&lt;span style="font-weight:400"&gt; Take thy throne within mortal flesh,&lt;/span&gt;&lt;span style="font-weight:400"&gt;&lt;br /&gt;&lt;/span&gt;&lt;span style="font-weight:400"&gt; Reign in power, descend in majesty.”&lt;/span&gt;&lt;/em&gt;&lt;/p&gt; &lt;p&gt;&lt;span style="font-weight:400"&gt;Small cuts formed all over me, causing me to scream in agony and thrash in my bindings. Blood slowly poured from all my cuts, magnetized towards the ritual glyphs as the droplets hit the floor below me.&lt;/span&gt;&lt;/p&gt; &lt;p&gt;&lt;em&gt;&lt;span style="font-weight:400"&gt;“O Mother of dynasties, O Keeper of bonds,&lt;/span&gt;&lt;span style="font-weight:400"&gt;&lt;br /&gt;&lt;/span&gt;&lt;span style="font-weight:400"&gt; Rule through this chosen spark,&lt;/span&gt;&lt;span style="font-weight:400"&gt;&lt;br /&gt;&lt;/span&gt;&lt;span style="font-weight:400"&gt; We break his chains, we mark his soul,&lt;/span&gt;&lt;span style="font-weight:400"&gt;&lt;br /&gt;&lt;/span&gt;&lt;span style="font-weight:400"&gt; That thou mayest rule, and we command.”&lt;/span&gt;&lt;/em&gt;&lt;/p&gt; &lt;p&gt;&lt;span style="font-weight:400"&gt;My body completely melted away in a blob of red, my consciousness barely remaining.&lt;/span&gt;&lt;/p&gt; &lt;p&gt;&lt;em&gt;&lt;span style="font-weight:400"&gt;“By this covenant, by this contract,&lt;/span&gt;&lt;span style="font-weight:400"&gt;&lt;br /&gt;&lt;/span&gt;&lt;span style="font-weight:400"&gt; By the price we pledge in blood and life,&lt;/span&gt;&lt;span style="font-weight:400"&gt;&lt;br /&gt;&lt;/span&gt;&lt;span style="font-weight:400"&gt; We summon thee, Sanguinaria!&lt;/span&gt;&lt;span style="font-weight:400"&gt;&lt;br /&gt;&lt;/span&gt;&lt;span style="font-weight:400"&gt; Appear, and be bound!”&lt;/span&gt;&lt;/em&gt;&lt;/p&gt; &lt;p&gt;&lt;span style="font-weight:400"&gt;All I could see was red; I felt intangible. Looking down, I had no arms, legs, or any body to speak of. I was a floating pair of eyes in a weirdly red chamber, as far as I could tell.&lt;/span&gt;&lt;/p&gt; &lt;p&gt;&lt;span style="font-weight:400"&gt;All at once, the walls of the room closed in on me, causing my vision to blur to black. I felt my eyelids and the rest of my body forming from whatever had just enclosed me. It took a few moments to adjust, but I could finally open my eyes.&lt;/span&gt;&lt;/p&gt; &lt;p&gt;&lt;span style="font-weight:400"&gt;Looking down on me could be described as nothing other than the queen of Hell. Her ethereal red skin shimmered slightly in the candlelight, two long thin black horns protruded from her forehead. Draped between them were wavy black bangs, the rest of her long hair tied into a crown braid, and a small, elegant crown adorned her head. Her sclera was impossibly black, her irises a glowing amber, and her pupils were predatory slits. I should be terrified… except I wasn’t; I felt comforted. She looked down on me not with the judgment I felt from ordinary people, but with a tangible feeling of mother’s love.&lt;/span&gt;&lt;/p&gt; &lt;p&gt;&lt;span style="font-weight:400"&gt;She ran her long fingers through my hair… it seemed much longer than it should be given how she managed to twist it with her index finger. When it came into view, I couldn’t help but gasp; it was no longer my usual mousey brown, now a dark black similar to the woman towering over me. Only now did I notice I was sprawled out on her lap this whole time.&lt;/span&gt;&lt;/p&gt; &lt;p&gt;&lt;span style="font-weight:400"&gt;I shot up from where I lay in surprise, before feeling unexpectedly off balance and bumping something on my back against the couch, causing me to wince.&lt;/span&gt;&lt;/p&gt; &lt;p&gt;&lt;span style="font-weight:400"&gt;She giggled. “Velith, my daughter. I’m overjoyed to make your acquaintance.” She addressed… me? Oddly, the name invoked the same sort of feeling one gets from within whenever their actual name is called.&lt;/span&gt;&lt;/p&gt; &lt;p&gt;&lt;span style="font-weight:400"&gt;I looked behind me, making sure she wasn’t speaking to someone else before noticing something even more shocking: I seemed to have sprouted wings.&lt;/span&gt;&lt;/p&gt; &lt;hr /&gt; &lt;p&gt; &lt;/p&gt; &lt;p&gt;&lt;span style="font-weight:400"&gt;The coven sisters watched the scene wide-eyed. Apart from Mistress Hayes, none of them had seen a demonic summoning before. Though most of them had practiced the dark arts, none had done anything as ‘magical’ as this, limited to simple familiar and utility spells; some of the elder witches knew basic defense and attack spells too, but nothing this flashy.&lt;/span&gt;&lt;/p&gt; &lt;p&gt;&lt;span style="font-weight:400"&gt;Even for Mistress Hayes - the coven’s leader - this was something of a new experience. The summoning ritual she had previously witnessed summoned a mere lesser demon. This one, however, would summon one of the great archdemons of Hell.&lt;/span&gt;&lt;/p&gt; &lt;p&gt;&lt;span style="font-weight:400"&gt;It took around 10 minutes for the globule of blood to solidify into a regal-looking demon. She resembled the demon depicted in their source’s heirloom painting, but had distinctly straighter hair, and she looked a little off in other ways, bearing a very slight resemblance to the vessel. She stirred in her sleep, and the coven waited with bated breath for her to awaken.&lt;/span&gt;&lt;/p&gt; &lt;hr /&gt; &lt;p&gt; &lt;/p&gt; &lt;p&gt;&lt;span style="font-weight:400"&gt;Despite my internal panic, I couldn’t help but act reserved, straightening my posture and looking back at the woman whose lap I had lain upon moments prior. “What… have you done to me?” I asked.&lt;/span&gt;&lt;/p&gt; &lt;p&gt;&lt;span style="font-weight:400"&gt;The woman leaned forward, resting her chin on her hand. “Nothing really. Just as children don’t pick who their parents are, neither did I pick who my child would be… If anything you can blame the coven that summoned you, but it makes no difference.” She paused for a moment, taking in the sight of me with a blissful smile. “What’s done is done.”&lt;/span&gt;&lt;/p&gt; &lt;p&gt;&lt;span style="font-weight:400"&gt;I crossed my arms. “That doesn’t change the fact that I’m not whoever this Velith person you mention is. I’m….” &lt;/span&gt;&lt;/p&gt; &lt;p&gt;&lt;span style="font-weight:400"&gt;Who was I? I couldn’t remember my name from before. Now that I thought about it, I’d forgotten my parents’ names as well… “I… I don’t seem to be able to remember.”&lt;/span&gt;&lt;/p&gt; &lt;p&gt;&lt;span style="font-weight:400"&gt;The woman claiming to be my mother shrugged and shook her head. “I’ve heard most don’t. Regardless, Velith is the name I’ve chosen for you, so that’s undoubtedly who you are.”&lt;/span&gt;&lt;/p&gt; &lt;p&gt;&lt;span style="font-weight:400"&gt;I pinched the bridge of my nose, flinching slightly when the hand in question was of a crimson matching that of the other woman. Well, I didn’t seem to have much choice even if it was embarrassing to go by a girl’s name, and even when I tried to think up a new name to go by, I forgot it only a moment later. “What should I call you, then?” I asked, shyly glancing toward the mysterious woman.&lt;/span&gt;&lt;/p&gt; &lt;p&gt;&lt;span style="font-weight:400"&gt;“Mother, of course!” An excited, decidedly not queen-like smile plastered her face. Before she frowned in thought. “Others, however, refer to me as Sanguinaria, Archdemoness of Hell, ruler of the domains of aristocracy, blood lineage, royalty, and domination.” She stood and did an immaculate curtsey, unbecoming of her, if only for the fact that I felt innately undeserving of her respect. While performing the curtsey, I noticed Sanguinaria wince halfway through her action.&lt;/span&gt;&lt;/p&gt; &lt;p&gt;&lt;span style="font-weight:400"&gt;She sat back down and warned, “Try not to show deference to those below your standing as I just did. It will be unpleasant for you, as useful of a tool as it may be.” She raised her hand, and a steaming hot cup of tea appeared in her hand as she gently sipped at it.&lt;/span&gt;&lt;/p&gt; &lt;p&gt;&lt;span style="font-weight:400"&gt;My mind was churning blanks. On the one hand, I logically couldn’t understand anything that was happening, but emotionally and instinctually, it all made more sense than it should.&lt;/span&gt;&lt;/p&gt; &lt;p&gt;&lt;span style="font-weight:400"&gt;For example, the woman in front of me definitely wasn’t the mom I remembered, but at the same time, she felt more like my mother than my old mom ever did, even in all my memories. Also, after hearing it a few times and repeating it in my head, I distinctly felt the name Velith was undoubtedly mine, even if I remembered that it wasn’t my name before.&lt;/span&gt;&lt;/p&gt; &lt;p&gt;&lt;span style="font-weight:400"&gt;There was one thing nagging me most, though: “&lt;/span&gt;&lt;i&gt;&lt;span style="font-weight:400"&gt;Why am I your daughter instead of your son?”&lt;/span&gt;&lt;/i&gt;&lt;/p&gt; &lt;/div&gt;</description>
