      <description>&lt;div class="wi_fic_desc" property="description"&gt;&lt;p&gt;After his last exhausting concert, 23-year-old Phum Jiaranai leaves Bangkok’s stage lights behind, taking his 18-year-old sister May, who he used to see as his brother, to their late mother’s small countryside home. The siblings haven’t lived together in over five years, ever since May moved abroad to live with their father, and both carrying scars from their time apart.&lt;/p&gt; &lt;p&gt;For May, England was a nightmare of loneliness, bullying, and isolation due to her gender identity. Made worse by the fact that no one, not even her father, seemed to see how much she was hurting. For Phum, every screaming crowd only made him feel the absence of the one person he wanted to protect the most.&lt;/p&gt; &lt;p&gt;Now reunited for barely a month, Phum is determined to be someone May can lean on again, even as his own career anxiety pushes him toward quitting the idol life entirely. May, guarded but warm, isn’t sure how to open up. But the slow rhythms of country life, a creaky old house full of memories, and a nosy neighbor might just give them the space they need.&lt;/p&gt; &lt;/div&gt;&lt;hr&gt;&lt;h3&gt;&lt;a href="https://www.scribblehub.com/read/1791253-lost-in-the-country/chapter/1791296/"&gt;&lt;div class="chapter-title"&gt;Chapter 1: Back to the House with the Blue Eaves&lt;/div&gt;&lt;/a&gt;&lt;/h3&gt;&lt;div class="chp_raw" id="chp_raw"&gt;&lt;p&gt;They reached the edge of town just as the sky softened to milk and honey. The road narrowed to a lane where tall grasses leaned in and the air smelled faintly of earth and rain that hadn’t fallen yet.&lt;/p&gt; &lt;p&gt;Phum rolled the truck window down; the wind combed his loose curls and carried the kind of quiet he hasn't had in months. With no stage hands shouting call times, no bass checking the walls, and no fans gathering like a sea. Just birds, cicadas, and leaves making their own sort of slow applause.&lt;/p&gt; &lt;p&gt;“Looks smaller than I remember,” May murmured, forehead resting lightly against the glass.&lt;/p&gt; &lt;p&gt;“Things always do when compared to how we remember them as kids.” Phum said. His voice was low and warm, as if he didn’t want to wake anything that could be sleeping at this.&lt;/p&gt; &lt;p&gt;They turned onto the gravel path and there it was: the little house with the blue eaves, the paint sun bleached to a lighter shade, the porch slanted just slightly, the front steps sagging from years of weather and lack of care. The mango tree out front had grown wilder than the picture he had in his head. The branches stretched in every angle, throwing soft patchy shade across the over grown green and the dirt path up to the house.&lt;/p&gt; &lt;p&gt;Phum cut the engine. The sudden stillness rang in his ears.&lt;/p&gt; &lt;p&gt;“Home,” he said, half to himself.&lt;/p&gt; &lt;p&gt;They didn’t move for a moment. May’s fingers found the strap of her bag and pinched, a small habit she’d picked up somewhere in the last five years. Something to hold when everything else felt too big. He’d noticed it during the month they’d been back together, in Bangkok. When schedules ended and he came home to find her awake on the couch, the TV flickering at low volume, the apartment too quiet for either of them to sleep well. He’d promised himself then that he would be the one she could lean on again. No matter what that meant, no matter what it cost.&lt;/p&gt; &lt;p&gt;He climbed out first and came around to her side, opening the door like they were still small and this was still a great occasion. “Ready, Matthew-?”&lt;/p&gt; &lt;p&gt;He froze.&lt;/p&gt; &lt;p&gt;“-May. Sorry.” His eyes were quickly filled with apology. “I didn’t mean-”&lt;/p&gt; &lt;p&gt;May’s smile curled gently, almost amused. “It’s fine. I know it’ll take a while. It would only hurt if you said it on purpose.”&lt;/p&gt; &lt;p&gt;“Still,” he said quietly, “I’ll do better.”&lt;/p&gt; &lt;p&gt;“I know.”&lt;/p&gt; &lt;p&gt;When Phum pushed on the front door the wood stuck at first, then yielded with a teeth gritting creak. The house smelled like old wood and humidity. But also a few old memories. Tea leaves in a tin that no one had opened, soap from a bar that still waited by the sink as if their mother might come back from the market any minute. The light through the thin curtains was gold and soft and full of dust motes drifting like snow that just wont fall.&lt;/p&gt; &lt;p&gt;They stood in the living room space without speaking. The wicker sofa sagged where Phum and May had once bounced hard enough to earn a stern look and a smothered laugh. The low shelf still held the blue ceramic fish their mother used to hide sweets in, one of the fins chipped, the lid slightly crooked and out of place. On the far wall, a small cluster of frames; a baby in a puffy hat and mouth open with delight, May. A toddler with stubborn thick curls and scraped knees, eyes wide and already too tall for his age, Phum. A woman with a bright, brave smile and a hand on each of their shoulders, like she could anchor them to the earth by touch alone.&lt;/p&gt; &lt;p&gt;“She loved that dress,” May said, stepping closer to one photo. “She said the flowers brought luck.”&lt;/p&gt; &lt;p&gt;“And you hated the sleeves,” Phum remembered. “Too itchy.”&lt;/p&gt; &lt;p&gt;“You cried more than I did,” she countered, and the look they shared was the kind that folds time in half.&lt;/p&gt; &lt;p&gt;Phum smiled, but tears already sat in the edges of his lashes. Refusing to blink so his tears won't spill. Rubbing his thumb and forefinger over his eyes, he cleared his throat. May smiled gently and rubbed his back, "See? Crybaby."&lt;/p&gt; &lt;p&gt;That comment got a chuckle out of him.&lt;/p&gt; &lt;p&gt;They moved together through the house as if retracing footsteps their bodies still remembered. The kitchen is small. The tiles are chipped and the window over the sink were covered in grime with peeling paint. The narrow hall that always carried the soft cool of mornings, and the deep warmth of the afternoons. The sowing room at the back where their mother used to hum while mending clothes. Phum paused there, his fingers mindlessly grazing the doorframe. A breath caught in his chest and stayed.&lt;/p&gt; &lt;p&gt;“We’ll make it nice,” he said finally, because he needed the sentence to end somewhere hopeful. “I’ll start with the windows. They’ll open clean, with no more sticking. New screen mesh so the night breeze can come through. We’ll make it… ours.”&lt;/p&gt; &lt;p&gt;May nodded. She ran a fingertip over the edge of a low table, drawing a line in the dust, then wiped it away with the hem of her shirt. “It already feels like ours.”&lt;/p&gt; &lt;p&gt;A voice drifted in from outside, just over the fence. “Jiaranai children?”&lt;/p&gt; &lt;p&gt;They both looked up. At the low wooden gate stood a woman with hair the color of soft ash and a dress with tiny flowers speckled all over. She held a basket at her hip like it had grown there.&lt;/p&gt; &lt;p&gt;“Auntie Mali,” Phum said, recognition blooming. A time of being small and looked after came to mind. He hurried across the house to the porch and down the steps, slowing at the gate. “Yes, it’s us. Phum and May.”&lt;/p&gt; &lt;p&gt;“I thought so,” she said, the way people do when they’ve secretly been hoping all along. “I told my granddaughter you’d be coming soon, and she said I was making up stories again.” Her eyes crinkled. “Come, let me look.”&lt;/p&gt; &lt;p&gt;They stepped closer. Auntie Mali set the basket on the gate post and took May’s hands in both of hers, then Phum’s, as if confirming a rumor with her palms. “Grown so tall,” she said to Phum, awe and fondness in equal measure. “Like your father’s side, all legs and trouble.”&lt;/p&gt; &lt;p&gt;Phum laughed awkwardly at the mention if his father. “Auntie-”&lt;/p&gt; &lt;p&gt;“And you,” she said to May, her voice softening. “You used to be such a tomboy when you were little, I thought you were a boy. Look at you, now such a beautiful young woman. You carry your mother here.” A fingertip brushed the space between May’s brows, where worry sometimes pinched. “And here.” She tapped over May’s heart, quick and light, like a blessing.&lt;/p&gt; &lt;p&gt;May bowed her head, the smile different now. Smaller but warmer too.&lt;/p&gt; &lt;p&gt;“I brought sticky rice cakes,” Auntie Mali said while lifting the basket. “They are not fancy, but first days need something sweet.” She glanced past them, into the dim living room, as if checking whether the house approved. “You can call if you need anything! A ladder, a hammer, a recipe... Gossip.”&lt;/p&gt; &lt;p&gt;“We’ll probably need all four,” Phum said with a grin.&lt;/p&gt; &lt;p&gt;“Good! It’s terrible to need nothing.” She pushed the basket into his arms and shooed them gently. “Eat, then rest. Or work. Either way, don’t be too proud to ask for anything.”&lt;/p&gt; &lt;p&gt;When she returned to across the road, there was a scent of jasmine and a feeling of being claimed by the neighborhood left behind. Phum and May stood on the porch and breathed like the morning had finally arrived properly.&lt;/p&gt; &lt;p&gt;He set the basket on the kitchen counter and began opening cabinets to see what was left behind. “We’ll do a first sweep,” he said, snapping a light on and off, listening to the bulb hum. “Check water, check fuses, check the well pump.” He reached for the old handle by the sink, the tap coughed and spat, then released a thin stream came out that soon turned steady. “Not bad,” he said, pleased.&lt;/p&gt; &lt;p&gt;“And I’ll do a first wipe,” May said, rolling her sleeves to the elbow. “Dust, counters, shelves. Let’s map what needs buying, and what can be fixed.”&lt;/p&gt; &lt;p&gt;They fell into work naturally, without much planning, falling back into a dance that felt like they’d practiced years ago. Phum hauled boxes from the pickup truck and stacked them by room, calling out labels, “Kitchen, May’s room, linen closet," while May moved fluidly through the small spaces, hands busy, eyes bright when she found something worth keeping and gently setting it aside. When he needed a second pair of hands to steady a stubborn window, she was there. When she needed a heavier lift, he was already coming down the hall.&lt;/p&gt; &lt;p&gt;They were still a little rough around the edges. Just tiny edge, though. The places where the last five years had drawn new lines: the way May’s smile sometimes never reached her eyes when strangers were present; the way Phum’s laughter, big and easy, occasionally hollowed in the middle when his mind began thinking about matters that should be behind him now. He caught himself checking on her too often. "You okay?" Sometimes biting the question back, worried the constant concern would be more burdensome. He didn’t want to crowd her. He wanted to be solid, the way their mother had been: warm and certain and there.&lt;/p&gt; &lt;p&gt;Just be there.&lt;/p&gt; &lt;p&gt;At noon they sat on the porch steps with two of Auntie Mali’s rice cakes unwrapped on their knees. The cake was sweet, coconut rich, the kind of simple that they craved. A breeze threaded the mango leaves, stitching light across the yard, bringing breath to the somewhat stagnant air.&lt;/p&gt; &lt;p&gt;“Do you remember,” May asked, squinting into the green, “when Mom would hang sheets on that line and we’d run under them? You’d pretend to be a ghost.”&lt;/p&gt; &lt;p&gt;“I was very convincing,” Phum said with a smile.&lt;/p&gt; &lt;p&gt;“You tripped over the basin and cried.”&lt;/p&gt; &lt;p&gt;“I was extremely convincing?”&lt;/p&gt; &lt;p&gt;She laughed, and it was like a window opening. He stored the sound away in his heart, like a thing he might need later.&lt;/p&gt; &lt;p&gt;After they ate, he went hunting for the toolkit and found it in the back room beneath a stack of old newspapers and a plastic bag of clothespins. He strapped the leather belt around his hips and lifted the first sash window with his shoulder, testing the slide. “We can loosen this,” he called.&lt;/p&gt; &lt;p&gt;“I’ll get a cloth,” May said. “And a list.”&lt;/p&gt; &lt;p&gt;He watched her cross the room and felt that old, fierce swell of wanting to build a world around her where she wouldn’t have to brace herself for impact. In the month since they’d come back together, he’d learned how much had been taken from her by small daily cruelties, the kind that leave no bruise you can point to. He hated those invisible hands more than anything. He wasn’t sure he believed in fate or fairness, but he believed in this: he could learn how to build a house and learn who his sister truly is. He could put his body between her and the wind. He could crush any new hands under the weight of his foot.&lt;/p&gt; &lt;p&gt;He set the window down gently and looked over. “Tea?”&lt;/p&gt; &lt;p&gt;“Sure,” May said.&lt;/p&gt; &lt;p&gt;They moved to the kitchen, shoulder brushing shoulder in the narrow space. The kettle clicked to life; she measured leaves the way their mother had taught her, palm and memory, no spoons. While Phum boiled the water in a kettle. When she poured, the steam rose like a small ceremony. Familiar.&lt;/p&gt; &lt;p&gt;“Tomorrow,” Phum said softly while sitting on a creaking stool at the island counter in the kitchen, “I’ll run to town. We’ll get more mesh, screws, light bulbs. Maybe a fan that doesn’t sound like a motor.”&lt;/p&gt; &lt;p&gt;“Curtains,” May added. “Soft ones. Not too thick.”&lt;/p&gt; &lt;p&gt;“And a lock that doesn’t stick.”&lt;/p&gt; &lt;p&gt;“And a welcome mat that isn’t a tripping hazard.”&lt;/p&gt; &lt;p&gt;He grinned. “Bossy.”&lt;/p&gt; &lt;p&gt;“I'm a visionary.”&lt;/p&gt; &lt;p&gt;Phum shoved his shoulder into her and she immediately retaliated, almost knocking him off his stool, making both of them burst into laughter.&lt;/p&gt; &lt;p&gt;They sipped in silence for a while until a motorbike buzzed past and faded outside, the sound swallowed by the heat. In the living room, Phum's small radio played an old love song thinly through static.&lt;/p&gt; &lt;p&gt;“Yesterday already feels far,” May said, not looking at him.&lt;/p&gt; &lt;p&gt;He knew what she meant; the roar and burn of his last concert, the crowd like a wave that was drowning him; the dressing room lights that used to thrill and lately only flickered against something anxious inside his chest. He had stumbled back into that dressing room drenched in sweat from both performing and something else, practically falling over a chair. His breathing was rushed like he couldn't get enough air. May had run in after him and told everyone to get out. Being his only anchor while his vision pulsed. That was the third time in his life he had ever had a panic attack.&lt;/p&gt; &lt;p&gt;He wasn’t sure who he was if he wasn’t on a stage, but right now, in this kitchen, with this tea and this girl who was his first and last family, he was closer to himself than he’d been in months.&lt;/p&gt; &lt;p&gt;“It can stay far away,” he said. “We’re here.”&lt;/p&gt; &lt;p&gt;May set her cup down and leaned her shoulder against his. The touch was light but steady. He didn’t move, afraid to break the moment by wanting too much from it.&lt;/p&gt; &lt;p&gt;“Thank you,” she said.&lt;/p&gt; &lt;p&gt;“For what?”&lt;/p&gt; &lt;p&gt;“For the windows,” she said. “For the mesh. For… everything.”&lt;/p&gt; &lt;p&gt;His throat tightened. He cleared it with a small, useless cough. “We’ll make it good,” he said. “You can rely on me, okay? That’s the plan.”&lt;/p&gt; &lt;p&gt;May’s eyes shone in a way that wasn’t only from the light.&lt;/p&gt; &lt;p&gt;“I know,” she said.&lt;/p&gt; &lt;p&gt;They finished their tea. The afternoon stretched out, full of small tasks and the promise of clean sheets and a first night full of crickets. They picked up rags and a screwdriver, ready to clean and rebuild this house by one dust and one screw at a time. And when the breeze came again, it moved straight through the rooms as if the house had been waiting all these years for the exact sound of their two voices together.&lt;/p&gt; &lt;/div&gt;</description>
