    <item>
      <title>Hawks &amp;#038; Violets</title>
      <author> TernUnfettered </author>
      <link>https://www.scribblehub.com/series/1762803/hawks--violets/</link>
      <comments>https://www.scribblehub.com/read/1762803-hawks--violets/chapter/1762806/#comments</comments>
      <guid isPermaLink="false">e0c0891d664b6d67589d0de6fb285b4497cab677</guid>
      <pubDate>Sun, 17 Aug 2025 00:00:00 +0000</pubDate>
      <description>&lt;div class="wi_fic_desc" property="description"&gt;&lt;p&gt;High school can feel like a jungle for Hawk, living as a socially awkward closeted teenager, having to balance her social life while keeping up with class, plus trying to hide her very embarrassing feelings from her crush. It's a lot of work. Almost harder than managing her sworn duty to her home clan of monster hunters, and her secret assignment to protect the innocent from the abnormal amount of hidden terrors haunting the small town of Hallwood.&lt;/p&gt; &lt;p&gt;Almost.&lt;/p&gt; &lt;/div&gt;&lt;hr&gt;&lt;h3&gt;&lt;a href="https://www.scribblehub.com/read/1762803-hawks--violets/chapter/1762806/"&gt;&lt;div class="chapter-title"&gt;Chapter 1 – Daemonica Lilim&lt;/div&gt;&lt;/a&gt;&lt;/h3&gt;&lt;div class="chp_raw" id="chp_raw"&gt;&lt;p&gt;&lt;span style="font-weight:400"&gt;The ticking of the clock bothered me. &lt;/span&gt;&lt;/p&gt; &lt;p&gt;&lt;span style="font-weight:400"&gt;Each and every one of those ticks echoed in my mind, compounding and compounding. It got on my nerves, it really did. It was the imperfect quietness of it all. Like it was scientifically engineered to cause me unnerve.&lt;/span&gt;&lt;/p&gt; &lt;p&gt;&lt;span style="font-weight:400"&gt;I’m forced to remain hyper aware of my own presence, of my surroundings. In this crowd of strangers my age, one would think we were all sheep being shepherded into slaughter. Well, almost, depending on how someone would look at things…&lt;/span&gt;&lt;/p&gt; &lt;p&gt;&lt;span style="font-weight:400"&gt;But my unnerving wait would soon end… In 3, 2, 1-&lt;/span&gt;&lt;/p&gt; &lt;p&gt;&lt;span style="font-weight:400"&gt;The bell rang.&lt;/span&gt;&lt;/p&gt; &lt;p&gt;&lt;span style="font-weight:400"&gt;The teenagers all around the classroom started to stand up and chatter amongst themselves. In between the noise, the teacher called out, “Make sure to finish the assignment before Monday!”&lt;/span&gt;&lt;/p&gt; &lt;p&gt;&lt;span style="font-weight:400"&gt;I doubted that many of them would listen, or even care, but I made a mental note of it as I went ahead and packed my things.&lt;/span&gt;&lt;/p&gt; &lt;p&gt;&lt;span style="font-weight:400"&gt;In an environment like this, I’d always found noise far more comfortable, particularly just in the background. The hustle and bustle of people’s daily lives around me. There was a sense of safety to it, like I would blend right in it. For better or worse, most people wouldn’t even notice my presence. Though there was also…&lt;/span&gt;&lt;/p&gt; &lt;p&gt;&lt;span style="font-weight:400"&gt;A large arm suddenly wrapped over my shoulder with a hearty laugh. “Hawk! Man, lemme tell ya, I was totally lost in that last assignment!”&lt;/span&gt;&lt;/p&gt; &lt;p&gt;&lt;span style="font-weight:400"&gt;Normally I would have been ready to reflexively deck whoever tried to suddenly touch me like this. But if it was Noah, I wouldn’t mind. Especially his... a-arm… so close…&lt;/span&gt;&lt;/p&gt; &lt;p&gt;&lt;span style="font-weight:400"&gt;“I-I always like algebra, so it didn’t take long for me to finish…” I responded in my usual tired voice, trying to hide my embarrassment. Working through logic and arithmetics was a soothing process for me, if anything. Though finishing the assignment early like that did lead to some minor frustration, being left with nothing but the ticking clock ringing in my ear.&lt;/span&gt;&lt;/p&gt; &lt;p&gt;&lt;span style="font-weight:400"&gt;“Oh really?” Noah smiled at me, causing a faint flutter in my heart. “Great! Maybe you could help me finish it!” He let go of me as we started to walk, which left me to internally sigh in disappointment. Oh well, it was nice while it lasted. But I made sure to pick up my step behind him.&lt;/span&gt;&lt;/p&gt; &lt;p&gt;&lt;span style="font-weight:400"&gt;“Um well, I’d love to help!” I quickly answered. “Maybe we could plan out a day or something where I could…”&lt;/span&gt;&lt;/p&gt; &lt;p&gt;&lt;span style="font-weight:400"&gt;Noah chuckled. “Nah, knowing you, we could probably wrap something like that up in a jiffy. We could even just get it over with during lunch!”&lt;/span&gt;&lt;/p&gt; &lt;p&gt;&lt;span style="font-weight:400"&gt;Yeah, it figured. That’d be a bit too easy. But it was an excuse to hang out either way, so I couldn’t be too bummed.&lt;/span&gt;&lt;/p&gt; &lt;p&gt;&lt;span style="font-weight:400"&gt;Now if only he could one day stop seeing me as a guy, and treating me like some bro…&lt;/span&gt;&lt;/p&gt; &lt;p&gt;&lt;span style="font-weight:400"&gt;It made sense, considering that’s what it said on all the papers, and how I’d been living for my entire life. But that wasn’t what I wanted, deep down. I knew it wasn’t in the cards to ever tell people, let alone do anything about it, but… I’m pretty sure I’m actually a girl. Transgender specifically, although closeted. &lt;/span&gt;&lt;/p&gt; &lt;p&gt;&lt;span style="font-weight:400"&gt;In that sense, I couldn’t really blame Noah. He was straight as far as I was aware, which was preferable if anything. It was just my own fault for losing the coinflip and getting stuck with a boy’s life. I just had to get myself fixed at some point.&lt;/span&gt;&lt;/p&gt; &lt;p&gt;&lt;span style="font-weight:400"&gt;But even then, I couldn’t be too mad if being stuck as a guy let me be close to him. Though it’s not like it isn’t a frustrating reminder either. Everything was strictly platonic.&lt;/span&gt;&lt;/p&gt; &lt;p&gt;&lt;span style="font-weight:400"&gt;It all just felt so perfect otherwise. Just imagine, a girl transfers from halfway across the globe, isolated, socially awkward, alone, and the perfect guy just shows up out of the blue to befriend her? Who would blame her? It’d be like something out of a fairy tale if my sex wasn’t getting in my way. I knew I wasn’t ready… I couldn’t just… &lt;/span&gt;&lt;i&gt;&lt;span style="font-weight:400"&gt;tell&lt;/span&gt;&lt;/i&gt;&lt;span style="font-weight:400"&gt; people to start treating me like a girl. I mean look at me!&lt;/span&gt;&lt;/p&gt; &lt;p&gt;&lt;span style="font-weight:400"&gt;B-But maybe the day will come… Where I’d finally be a girl. And if we were still together by that point, he might stop seeing me as some guy. H-He might think I’m pretty, that I make for a better girl than any crummy boy! And maybe then could I confess my feelings! Then he might take me as his girlfriend, and he’ll swoop me up and-!&lt;/span&gt;&lt;/p&gt; &lt;p&gt;&lt;span style="font-weight:400"&gt;Aw crap, I was letting my fantasies distract me, what was Noah talking about?&lt;/span&gt;&lt;/p&gt; &lt;p&gt;&lt;span style="font-weight:400"&gt;“-So yeah, that’s essentially the entire lore and backstory behind the first season of Star Trek.”&lt;/span&gt;&lt;/p&gt; &lt;p&gt;&lt;span style="font-weight:400"&gt;God, he’s so perfect.&lt;/span&gt;&lt;/p&gt; &lt;p&gt;&lt;span style="font-weight:400"&gt;“Hey, maybe I should watch it someday.” I commented.&lt;/span&gt;&lt;/p&gt; &lt;p&gt;&lt;span style="font-weight:400"&gt;“You should!” Noah replied, looking at me with that smile of his. “Seriously dude! It’s &lt;/span&gt;&lt;i&gt;&lt;span style="font-weight:400"&gt;so&lt;/span&gt;&lt;/i&gt;&lt;span style="font-weight:400"&gt; good!”&lt;/span&gt;&lt;/p&gt; &lt;p&gt;&lt;span style="font-weight:400"&gt;If he liked it, it probably was. It’s not like we’d known each other for too long, but we had some common interests in things. I got the sense he had good taste. I’d liked that one manga he'd recommended, at least.&lt;/span&gt;&lt;/p&gt; &lt;p&gt; &lt;/p&gt; &lt;hr /&gt; &lt;p&gt; &lt;/p&gt; &lt;p&gt;&lt;span style="font-weight:400"&gt;By the time we both sat down in the cafeteria, the dining hall was bustling. They were serving some kind of fish for dinner. It smelled bad, which reminded me of home. &lt;/span&gt;&lt;/p&gt; &lt;p&gt;&lt;span style="font-weight:400"&gt;Jason was arguing with Soph at our usual table, the latter coolly leaning back with her arms crossed as she rolled her eyes. &lt;/span&gt;&lt;/p&gt; &lt;p&gt;&lt;span style="font-weight:400"&gt;“Noah! Tell her this thing’s legit!” Jason called out.&lt;/span&gt;&lt;/p&gt; &lt;p&gt;&lt;span style="font-weight:400"&gt;“Dude, shut up…” Soph groaned.&lt;/span&gt;&lt;/p&gt; &lt;p&gt;&lt;span style="font-weight:400"&gt;“What’s this about?” Noah asked.&lt;/span&gt;&lt;/p&gt; &lt;p&gt;&lt;span style="font-weight:400"&gt;Jason flashed his phone to Noah. Sitting next to him, I got a good look too. It was a blurry picture of some forest, and… was there anything else? It was hard to tell.&lt;/span&gt;&lt;/p&gt; &lt;p&gt;&lt;span style="font-weight:400"&gt;He pointed his finger at a spot. “Tell me you don’t see a sasquatch right here!”&lt;/span&gt;&lt;/p&gt; &lt;p&gt;&lt;span style="font-weight:400"&gt;Noah peered his eyes for a couple of seconds, “Uhh, not sure…”&lt;/span&gt;&lt;/p&gt; &lt;p&gt;&lt;span style="font-weight:400"&gt;“He’s right there!” Jason pointed again, more aggressively. He pulled his phone back to zoom in a bit better, then showed us again. “See?!”&lt;/span&gt;&lt;/p&gt; &lt;p&gt;&lt;span style="font-weight:400"&gt;“There’s no such thing.” Soph bluntly remarked.&lt;/span&gt;&lt;/p&gt; &lt;p&gt;&lt;span style="font-weight:400"&gt;“I dunno… Feels like it could be anything,” Noah commented, looking at the picture like he was still trying to make sense of what he was seeing. “This a new photo?”&lt;/span&gt;&lt;/p&gt; &lt;p&gt;&lt;span style="font-weight:400"&gt;Jason nodded, “It is. And you wouldn’t believe it… It was taken right here, ten miles west of Hallwood!”&lt;/span&gt;&lt;/p&gt; &lt;p&gt;&lt;span style="font-weight:400"&gt;Soph leaned forward on her arm and flipped on a smirk, “I thought Bigfoot was only all the way up in the northwest?”&lt;/span&gt;&lt;/p&gt; &lt;p&gt;&lt;span style="font-weight:400"&gt;Jason adjusted his glasses, “&lt;/span&gt;&lt;i&gt;&lt;span style="font-weight:400"&gt;Sasquatch&lt;/span&gt;&lt;/i&gt;&lt;span style="font-weight:400"&gt;,” he corrected. “This isn’t just one cryptid, it’s a potential species! They don’t necessarily isolate themselves in the northwest, some might be spreading out all the way over here!”&lt;/span&gt;&lt;/p&gt; &lt;p&gt;&lt;span style="font-weight:400"&gt;“Man, that’d be interesting.” Noah leaned back. “But Soph’s right, pretty sure these guys don’t exist. I bet someone’s just trying to get money or attention.”&lt;/span&gt;&lt;/p&gt; &lt;p&gt;&lt;span style="font-weight:400"&gt;“Oh yeah? Well I’ve set up an interview with the guy who took this pic! I’ll bring you guys more evidence tomorrow, just you watch!”&lt;/span&gt;&lt;/p&gt; &lt;p&gt;&lt;span style="font-weight:400"&gt;“Heh, good luck with that.” Soph remarked.&lt;/span&gt;&lt;/p&gt; &lt;p&gt;&lt;span style="font-weight:400"&gt;Finally, Noah looked at me. “Hey Hawk, what do you think?”&lt;/span&gt;&lt;/p&gt; &lt;p&gt;&lt;span style="font-weight:400"&gt;“H-Huh?” I almost jolted. I wasn’t expecting the question to be redirected to me.&lt;/span&gt;&lt;/p&gt; &lt;p&gt;&lt;span style="font-weight:400"&gt;“Bigfoot, sasquatch or whatever.” He continued. “You think it’s legit?”&lt;/span&gt;&lt;/p&gt; &lt;p&gt;&lt;span style="font-weight:400"&gt;That question was a complicated one, I wasn’t sure what I could really say about it besides the obvious already stated by the others. Though there was one thing that came to mind…&lt;/span&gt;&lt;/p&gt; &lt;p&gt;&lt;span style="font-weight:400"&gt;“I-I guess…” I began. “More than anything, I just hope it doesn’t hurt anyone. If it’s actually wandering around, I mean. If it makes it to town, what would happen? I don’t know if I’d feel safe with… You know.”&lt;/span&gt;&lt;/p&gt; &lt;p&gt;&lt;span style="font-weight:400"&gt;As I paused, Soph snorted out a quick laugh, “That’s almost adorable.”&lt;/span&gt;&lt;/p&gt; &lt;p&gt;&lt;span style="font-weight:400"&gt;“Huh? What?”&lt;/span&gt;&lt;/p&gt; &lt;p&gt;&lt;span style="font-weight:400"&gt;“Hawk, no one’s gonna be in any danger.” Noah chuckled. “I mean, come on. It’s just one ape guy. Even if he shows up, that’s nothing against stuff like, I dunno, an army.”&lt;/span&gt;&lt;/p&gt; &lt;p&gt;&lt;span style="font-weight:400"&gt;“The government wouldn’t help.” Jason interrupted. “They have a vested interest in keeping sasquatches alive in order to fund their anti-conspiracy propaganda.”&lt;/span&gt;&lt;/p&gt; &lt;p&gt;&lt;span style="font-weight:400"&gt;“Okay but even then,” Noah continued. “Between our local authorities and everyone in town, there’s nothing to actually worry about. And if worst comes to worst? You’d have us!” He smiled that stupid cheesy smile of his.&lt;/span&gt;&lt;/p&gt; &lt;p&gt;&lt;span style="font-weight:400"&gt;Soph snorted again. “Like you’d stand a chance. You’re not some anime protagonist.”&lt;/span&gt;&lt;/p&gt; &lt;p&gt;&lt;span style="font-weight:400"&gt;“You don’t know that!” He hit back with a laugh. “For all we know, I’ll awaken to my nen or whatever any day now! I’ll kick all the butts!”&lt;/span&gt;&lt;/p&gt; &lt;p&gt;&lt;span style="font-weight:400"&gt;“I-I didn’t mean it like that!” I responded, trying not to sound too flustered by his earlier comment. “I mean… about everyone else! Even if it was stopped, ‘one ape guy’ could still hurt a lot of people.”&lt;/span&gt;&lt;/p&gt; &lt;p&gt;&lt;span style="font-weight:400"&gt;“Oh yeah, get what you mean.” Noah thought to himself with a nod.&lt;/span&gt;&lt;/p&gt; &lt;p&gt;&lt;span style="font-weight:400"&gt;“Eh, it’s not actually something to freak out about.” Soph shrugged, leaning both arms and head down on the table. “You’d need to believe in the damn thing in the first place.”&lt;/span&gt;&lt;/p&gt; &lt;p&gt;&lt;span style="font-weight:400"&gt;“I can order a stock of silver bullets off of amazon.” Jason added. “I’ve no proof, but there’s a chance they might belong to the same genus as werewolves, so it’s worth a shot.”&lt;/span&gt;&lt;/p&gt; &lt;p&gt;&lt;span style="font-weight:400"&gt;“You? Holding a gun?” Soph smirked. “Those arms?”&lt;/span&gt;&lt;/p&gt; &lt;p&gt;&lt;span style="font-weight:400"&gt;“I’ll work out if it’s for science, and if I can bring proof of a sasquatch to the world.”&lt;/span&gt;&lt;/p&gt; &lt;p&gt;&lt;span style="font-weight:400"&gt;“Um, good luck with that!” I offered. &lt;/span&gt;&lt;/p&gt; &lt;p&gt;&lt;span style="font-weight:400"&gt;Jason cocked a brow at me.&lt;/span&gt;&lt;/p&gt; &lt;p&gt;&lt;span style="font-weight:400"&gt;“I didn’t mean that sarcastically!” I clarified. Was it so cruel to wish a friend good luck? I dunno, I thought he’d appreciate it with how often he’s put down for this type of stuff.&lt;/span&gt;&lt;/p&gt; &lt;p&gt;&lt;span style="font-weight:400"&gt;“Okay but seriously, this- Wait, look alive!” Soph interrupted herself, her eyes shooting off into the other end of the lunchroom.&lt;/span&gt;&lt;/p&gt; &lt;p&gt;&lt;span style="font-weight:400"&gt;“Huh? What is it-? Oh.” Jason’s disappointment was evident by the tone of his ‘oh.’ “It’s just &lt;/span&gt;&lt;i&gt;&lt;span style="font-weight:400"&gt;her&lt;/span&gt;&lt;/i&gt;&lt;span style="font-weight:400"&gt;.”&lt;/span&gt;&lt;/p&gt; &lt;p&gt;&lt;span style="font-weight:400"&gt;“&lt;/span&gt;&lt;i&gt;&lt;span style="font-weight:400"&gt;The &lt;/span&gt;&lt;/i&gt;&lt;span style="font-weight:400"&gt;Lilianna Hertz.” Soph clarified, a grin creeping up on her face. “You guys hear she just dumped her latest boyfriend?”&lt;/span&gt;&lt;/p&gt; &lt;p&gt;&lt;span style="font-weight:400"&gt;She was one of the more popular girls in Hallwood High. Definitely very pretty, I’ll admit, but I struggled to see what others saw. Though maybe that was just my own lack of interest in the fairer sex. Between her long blond hair and her fashion choices often showing skin. I dunno, something about her just felt like a cliché to me.&lt;/span&gt;&lt;/p&gt; &lt;p&gt;&lt;span style="font-weight:400"&gt;Jason rolled his eyes. “Oh, give it up. She’s straight.”&lt;/span&gt;&lt;/p&gt; &lt;p&gt;&lt;span style="font-weight:400"&gt;“You don’t know that!” She hit back. “She could be bi! Or in denial! Why do you think she never stays with her little boyfriends for long?”&lt;/span&gt;&lt;/p&gt; &lt;p&gt;&lt;span style="font-weight:400"&gt;“It is downright depressing when I have to watch you act like this.” Jason shook his head.&lt;/span&gt;&lt;/p&gt; &lt;p&gt;&lt;span style="font-weight:400"&gt;“Let me dream!” Soph groaned.&lt;/span&gt;&lt;/p&gt; &lt;p&gt;&lt;span style="font-weight:400"&gt;“Just ask her out already.” Noah argued. “Even if she says no, you could just be done with it.”&lt;/span&gt;&lt;/p&gt; &lt;p&gt;&lt;span style="font-weight:400"&gt;“What? N-No, I can’t just-! Ugh, you guys don’t get it!”&lt;/span&gt;&lt;/p&gt; &lt;p&gt;&lt;span style="font-weight:400"&gt;I kinda did, though my situation was albeit a bit different. &lt;/span&gt;&lt;/p&gt; &lt;p&gt;&lt;span style="font-weight:400"&gt;Still, Lilianna did have my attention. A part of me definitely wondered what was up with her, if she actually-&lt;/span&gt;&lt;/p&gt; &lt;p&gt;&lt;span style="font-weight:400"&gt;Suddenly Soph’s eyes went wide and adjusted her gaze down to the table. “She’s looking this way!”&lt;/span&gt;&lt;/p&gt; &lt;p&gt;&lt;span style="font-weight:400"&gt;Wait, what? As I looked back at her, I realized Soph was right. Thankfully, not directly at me. Although, it wasn’t just that she was looking in our table’s direction, she was also walking over to us.&lt;/span&gt;&lt;/p&gt; &lt;p&gt;&lt;span style="font-weight:400"&gt;“Oh shit, is this the day-? I-I gotta scram, don’t tell her I was here!”&lt;/span&gt;&lt;/p&gt; &lt;p&gt;&lt;span style="font-weight:400"&gt;Before anyone could tell Soph that awkwardly running off to another table wouldn’t help her endeavours, she was off. And before the other three of us knew it, the woman of the hour was sitting down at our table.&lt;/span&gt;&lt;/p&gt; &lt;p&gt;&lt;span style="font-weight:400"&gt;“Um, hi?” Jason halfheartedly greeted, trying to sound as if she was unwelcome or intruding.&lt;/span&gt;&lt;/p&gt; &lt;p&gt;&lt;span style="font-weight:400"&gt;But she didn’t answer, instead her gaze was fixed on… Noah.&lt;/span&gt;&lt;/p&gt; &lt;p&gt;&lt;span style="font-weight:400"&gt;Uh-oh.&lt;/span&gt;&lt;/p&gt; &lt;p&gt;&lt;span style="font-weight:400"&gt;“What was your name again?”&lt;/span&gt;&lt;/p&gt; &lt;p&gt;&lt;span style="font-weight:400"&gt;Noah had been pretty unfazed by her entrance, so he was eating with his mouth full when she’d greeted him. “Huh? Oh yeah, I’m Noah.”&lt;/span&gt;&lt;/p&gt; &lt;p&gt;&lt;span style="font-weight:400"&gt;“Noah, ay?” She slowly nodded to herself, gingerly lifting an arm up to lightly stroke her chin. “You wouldn’t happen to be busy tomorrow, would you?”&lt;/span&gt;&lt;/p&gt; &lt;p&gt;&lt;span style="font-weight:400"&gt;“What?” Jason reacted in confusion.&lt;/span&gt;&lt;/p&gt; &lt;p&gt;&lt;span style="font-weight:400"&gt;“Huh? Uhh, I guess not. Why?” Noah responded, in an almost blissfully casual manner.&lt;/span&gt;&lt;/p&gt; &lt;p&gt;&lt;span style="font-weight:400"&gt;“Oh, nothing. Just wondering…”&lt;/span&gt;&lt;/p&gt; &lt;p&gt;&lt;span style="font-weight:400"&gt;“About what? You like HunterxHunter?” He asked, glancing down at his t shirt depicting the series logo.&lt;/span&gt;&lt;/p&gt; &lt;p&gt;&lt;span style="font-weight:400"&gt;Without answering, she just slid a small piece of paper across the table, “No, but I’m sure there are other things we could talk about.” Without so much as a room for another answer, she stood up and walked away.&lt;/span&gt;&lt;/p&gt; &lt;p&gt;&lt;span style="font-weight:400"&gt;Noah continued chewing his food, and swallowed. “Huh, that was weird.”&lt;/span&gt;&lt;/p&gt; &lt;p&gt;&lt;span style="font-weight:400"&gt;Soph’s footsteps thundered across the floor as she quickly arrived at our table, grabbing Noah by his shirt and shaking him. “DUDE WHAT THE HELL JUST HAPPENED?!”&lt;/span&gt;&lt;/p&gt; &lt;p&gt;&lt;span style="font-weight:400"&gt;“Huh?”&lt;/span&gt;&lt;/p&gt; &lt;p&gt;&lt;span style="font-weight:400"&gt;“Lemme see that!” She swiped the piece of paper. “Oh god, it’s actually her number. Noah, you lucky sunova…!”&lt;/span&gt;&lt;/p&gt; &lt;p&gt;&lt;span style="font-weight:400"&gt;Noah furrowed his brows, confused as he connected the dots together. “Wait… she was flirting with me?”&lt;/span&gt;&lt;/p&gt; &lt;p&gt;&lt;span style="font-weight:400"&gt;“Awfully promiscuous about it too.” Jason shrugged. “She knows we’re teenagers, right? Really feels like she was tryharding the whole seduction angle.”&lt;/span&gt;&lt;/p&gt; &lt;p&gt;&lt;span style="font-weight:400"&gt;“Damn, didn’t even notice.” Was all Noah responded with, and then he went right back to eating.&lt;/span&gt;&lt;/p&gt; &lt;p&gt;&lt;span style="font-weight:400"&gt;It led to a brief silence at the table. Even if I could tell Jason wasn’t all that interested in the topic, all three of us were pretty surprised that Noah was so quick to move on like that.&lt;/span&gt;&lt;/p&gt; &lt;p&gt;&lt;span style="font-weight:400"&gt;“Um…” I finally decided to voice my own thoughts, wanting to ask him the obvious question. “So are you going to do it? Go on a…?”&lt;/span&gt;&lt;/p&gt; &lt;p&gt;&lt;span style="font-weight:400"&gt;A part of me didn’t even want to finish the question. It made me nervous to think that someone had just asked out my crush like that, although it’s not like I had much of a chance myself.&lt;/span&gt;&lt;/p&gt; &lt;p&gt;&lt;span style="font-weight:400"&gt;As Noah pondered the question, I could tell Soph was staring daggers at him. Jason looked at him expectantly as well, though he seemed more bored by the entire topic.&lt;/span&gt;&lt;/p&gt; &lt;p&gt;&lt;span style="font-weight:400"&gt;“I dunno, isn’t she out of my league?”&lt;/span&gt;&lt;/p&gt; &lt;p&gt;&lt;span style="font-weight:400"&gt;“What?! Do it, you coward!” Soph responded by shaking him again.&lt;/span&gt;&lt;/p&gt; &lt;p&gt;&lt;span style="font-weight:400"&gt;I was also pretty disappointed by his answer. If anything, he was out of &lt;/span&gt;&lt;i&gt;&lt;span style="font-weight:400"&gt;her &lt;/span&gt;&lt;/i&gt;&lt;span style="font-weight:400"&gt;league.&lt;/span&gt;&lt;/p&gt; &lt;p&gt;&lt;span style="font-weight:400"&gt;“I thought you’d hate this.” Jason remarked towards Soph, half his attention on his food.&lt;/span&gt;&lt;/p&gt; &lt;p&gt;&lt;span style="font-weight:400"&gt;“No, this is perfect! It’s like having a man on the inside!” Soph explained, turning back to Noah. “You could ask her if she likes girls! Or… Or…! Or do something so stupid she swears off guys forever and gives girls a shot!”&lt;/span&gt;&lt;/p&gt; &lt;p&gt;&lt;span style="font-weight:400"&gt;Jason shook his head and let out a quick sigh.&lt;/span&gt;&lt;/p&gt; &lt;p&gt;&lt;span style="font-weight:400"&gt;“Well it’s not like I’d have to actually date her. Maybe I’ll call and we’ll just hang out for a bit and we talk about stuff.” Noah went on.&lt;/span&gt;&lt;/p&gt; &lt;p&gt;&lt;span style="font-weight:400"&gt;“That’d still be a date.” Jason remarked.&lt;/span&gt;&lt;/p&gt; &lt;p&gt;&lt;span style="font-weight:400"&gt;“Well it’d just be a one-off. It could be as friends.” Noah thought to himself. “But dunno, guess it wouldn’t hurt if things worked out. I’d love to meet a girl who was into me and liked the same stuff.”&lt;/span&gt;&lt;/p&gt; &lt;p&gt;&lt;span style="font-weight:400"&gt;There’s one sitting right next to you though!&lt;/span&gt;&lt;/p&gt; &lt;p&gt;&lt;span style="font-weight:400"&gt;“Hey Hawk, want me to give you a good word in, too?” He then asked.&lt;/span&gt;&lt;/p&gt; &lt;p&gt;&lt;span style="font-weight:400"&gt;“Huh?” I was surprised by the suggestion, though it made sense he’d think to ask that. For all he knew, I was just your stock socially awkward straight guy. “N-No thanks. You don’t have to think about me, just enjoy the date… or whatever you’d call it.”&lt;/span&gt;&lt;/p&gt; &lt;p&gt;&lt;span style="font-weight:400"&gt;“Do talk about me though!” Soph quickly interrupted to remind him.&lt;/span&gt;&lt;/p&gt; &lt;p&gt;&lt;span style="font-weight:400"&gt;Noah awkwardly ruffled his own hair and let out a short chuckle. “Well again, I dunno if I’d call it a date. But I guess it is something like that… Should probably get myself more ready.”&lt;/span&gt;&lt;/p&gt; &lt;p&gt;&lt;span style="font-weight:400"&gt;I nodded along as we finished eating lunch together. A part of me wanted to be happy for Noah, but I couldn’t help but be anxious, due to some particular issues.&lt;/span&gt;&lt;/p&gt; &lt;p&gt;&lt;span style="font-weight:400"&gt;The truth is I didn’t want or even need Noah's help here. I had a feeling I already knew how to get her attention.&lt;/span&gt;&lt;/p&gt; &lt;p&gt; &lt;/p&gt; &lt;hr /&gt; &lt;p&gt; &lt;/p&gt; &lt;p&gt;&lt;span style="font-weight:400"&gt;The time was 4:17 PM, after school.&lt;/span&gt;&lt;/p&gt; &lt;p&gt;&lt;span style="font-weight:400"&gt;Lilianna Hertz walked into the basement’s storage closet. It was small, but still had a relative amount of room, perfect for hiding things. As she closed the door behind her, her eyes and nose darted around, sniffing around until she opened a cardboard box in the corner. Lowering her hand into it, she lifted up a small incense.&lt;/span&gt;&lt;/p&gt; &lt;p&gt;&lt;span style="font-weight:400"&gt;“Huh? The hell is-?”&lt;/span&gt;&lt;/p&gt; &lt;p&gt;&lt;span style="font-weight:400"&gt;At that moment I stepped out of my hiding place, and fired my weapon.&lt;/span&gt;&lt;/p&gt; &lt;p&gt;&lt;span style="font-weight:400"&gt;The water squirted out, hitting Lilianna square on the back of her neck.&lt;/span&gt;&lt;/p&gt; &lt;p&gt;&lt;span style="font-weight:400"&gt;“AHH!” She yelled in pain, and a searing sound could be heard from her. Steam emitted from her neck, leaving it in a hot pink colour.&lt;/span&gt;&lt;/p&gt; &lt;p&gt;&lt;span style="font-weight:400"&gt;“WHAT THE FUCK JUST-?!” She turned around to face me, but froze when she spotted me pointing a water gun right up at her face.&lt;/span&gt;&lt;/p&gt; &lt;p&gt;&lt;span style="font-weight:400"&gt;“Daemonica Lilim.” I stated, calmly and assertively. “Hellspawn, usually located in the ring of lust. More commonly known… as a succubus. Protocol: Exterminate on sight.”&lt;/span&gt;&lt;/p&gt; &lt;p&gt;&lt;span style="font-weight:400"&gt;“What the hell are you talking ab-?”&lt;/span&gt;&lt;/p&gt; &lt;p&gt;&lt;span style="font-weight:400"&gt;I squirted more water, square on her forehead. Once again she screamed, searing in pain. The air got hot as more steam seemed to evaporate from her skin.&lt;/span&gt;&lt;/p&gt; &lt;p&gt;&lt;span style="font-weight:400"&gt;“This isn’t some boiling hot water or anything.” I explained. “It’s holy water, imported straight from the Vatican. There's no point pretending, the fact you’re reacting like this is all the proof I need.”&lt;/span&gt;&lt;/p&gt; &lt;p&gt;&lt;span style="font-weight:400"&gt;The steam from the back of her neck was slowly fading, visibly leaving that entire area now a different colour. I could tell that the pink hue wasn’t from some burn. It was her natural skin tone exposed, now that I’d seared a part of her disguise away.&lt;/span&gt;&lt;/p&gt; &lt;p&gt;&lt;span style="font-weight:400"&gt;Thick scowl on her face, she looked directly at me, as her eyes began glowing a striking pink hue. She was waiting for something, but I held my aim. Nothing happened. She seemed confused, “What? Why are you-?”&lt;/span&gt;&lt;/p&gt; &lt;p&gt;&lt;span style="font-weight:400"&gt;I fired another squirt at her before she could finish. This time on the left side of her head, revealing a dark purple hair colour, and a black horn creeping out. &lt;/span&gt;&lt;/p&gt; &lt;p&gt;&lt;span style="font-weight:400"&gt;“You…! You…!” She almost stammered as if still thinking of a response. She sounded scared, but my instincts told me otherwise. I kept the gun pointed right at her, almost point blank, which should deter her from making any sudden moves. “A-An exorcist?”&lt;/span&gt;&lt;/p&gt; &lt;p&gt;&lt;span style="font-weight:400"&gt;“Slayer,” I corrected, with trained confidence. "Haukur Ingvarsson, monster hunter of the northern Elfjord clan. But my friends call me Hawk here. I hunt and eliminate dangers to the world like you.”&lt;/span&gt;&lt;/p&gt; &lt;p&gt;&lt;span style="font-weight:400"&gt;Heaving from the pain, Lilianna fell to one of her knees. “Curses…! I’ve heard of your ilk, but how…?!”&lt;/span&gt;&lt;/p&gt; &lt;p&gt;&lt;span style="font-weight:400"&gt;“You’re not subtle.” I explained. Really, I’d suspected the possibility for a while now. Succubi seduce men and then get their nourishment by feeding off of their energy. Whether by sexual acts or just through basic skin contact. Whenever they invaded the mortal realm, they didn’t stick around for long without some sucker in tow. “The incense only confirmed it to me. You’re drawn to specific scents, you were bound to get curious once school was out and you thought no one was around.”&lt;/span&gt;&lt;/p&gt; &lt;p&gt;&lt;span style="font-weight:400"&gt;“You got too arrogant.” I went on, robotic in tone as I kept all my feelings in check. “The only reason you got to wander around for so long was luck. Had you taken enough energy from one of your boyfriends to kill them or leave them bedridden, I’d have acted sooner.”&lt;/span&gt;&lt;/p&gt; &lt;p&gt;&lt;span style="font-weight:400"&gt;“Hah…” Suddenly, Lilianna began letting out a cackle. “Hah! Hahah! ‘If I killed them,’ the nerve! I wasn’t planning on devouring any of those oafs! There was only one brood I needed, and I found it!”&lt;/span&gt;&lt;/p&gt; &lt;p&gt;&lt;span style="font-weight:400"&gt;I steadied my grip on the water gun. “What do you mean?”&lt;/span&gt;&lt;/p&gt; &lt;p&gt;&lt;span style="font-weight:400"&gt;“You haven’t realized it?” She grinned at me. “I doubt I’m the first! Clearly there’s a reason you’re here in the middle of nowhere! Elfjord clan? In the north? You’re a far way from home, brat!”&lt;/span&gt;&lt;/p&gt; &lt;p&gt;&lt;span style="font-weight:400"&gt;I didn’t answer.&lt;/span&gt;&lt;/p&gt; &lt;p&gt;&lt;span style="font-weight:400"&gt;“You’re drawn here for the same reason as me. This town’s home to a wellspring of energy! Powerful enough it’s not seen tens of thousands of miles from here! All within that &lt;/span&gt;&lt;i&gt;&lt;span style="font-weight:400"&gt;boy&lt;/span&gt;&lt;/i&gt;&lt;span style="font-weight:400"&gt;!”&lt;/span&gt;&lt;/p&gt; &lt;p&gt;&lt;span style="font-weight:400"&gt;“...Noah.” I added.&lt;/span&gt;&lt;/p&gt; &lt;p&gt;&lt;span style="font-weight:400"&gt;“Ah yes, that was his name!” Lilianna stood back up, talking about him in a mocking tone. “You barely know what you’ve gotten yourself into! I can feel it! The energy inside him is so dense I could pick up on the scent from miles! It may have taken me a while to pinpoint the exact source, but it won’t stop with me! The power within that boy might as well be a magnet to all the dangers hidden to the mortal world!”&lt;/span&gt;&lt;/p&gt; &lt;p&gt;&lt;span style="font-weight:400"&gt;“...I-I know.” I admitted.&lt;/span&gt;&lt;/p&gt; &lt;p&gt;&lt;span style="font-weight:400"&gt;“What?”&lt;/span&gt;&lt;/p&gt; &lt;p&gt;&lt;span style="font-weight:400"&gt;“I already figured it out. When I first got here.” I sighed. &lt;/span&gt;&lt;/p&gt; &lt;p&gt;&lt;span style="font-weight:400"&gt;That’s right, the source of an abnormal amount of supernatural sightings and rumours. When I got the file, I was told there was likely some type of phenomenon or energy focused in this town, drawing monsters and supernatural entities in. That’s why I was here. To find the source. I had been told those were usually magical artefacts, dimensional rifts, or a particularly devious monster. &lt;/span&gt;&lt;/p&gt; &lt;p&gt;&lt;span style="font-weight:400"&gt;But it wasn’t any of those things.&lt;/span&gt;&lt;/p&gt; &lt;p&gt;&lt;span style="font-weight:400"&gt;It was Noah. &lt;/span&gt;&lt;/p&gt; &lt;p&gt;&lt;span style="font-weight:400"&gt;Just some boy.&lt;/span&gt;&lt;/p&gt; &lt;p&gt;&lt;span style="font-weight:400"&gt;And he had no idea.&lt;/span&gt;&lt;/p&gt; &lt;p&gt;&lt;span style="font-weight:400"&gt;“Then why-?!” Lilianna questioned, before morphing into an uneasy smile. “But wait, then you understand, right? Our interests align! Let me have him, and I could take enough to end him. It would leave me with enough sustenance for years, no, decades even! And with him dead there won’t be a problem! Why not let him die in bliss, thinking he has a pretty girl under his arm? We can work together, if you spare-”&lt;/span&gt;&lt;/p&gt; &lt;p&gt;&lt;span style="font-weight:400"&gt;“No.” I interrupted.&lt;/span&gt;&lt;/p&gt; &lt;p&gt;&lt;span style="font-weight:400"&gt;“Wh-What?” &lt;/span&gt;&lt;/p&gt; &lt;p&gt;&lt;span style="font-weight:400"&gt;“I… I can’t have that.”&lt;/span&gt;&lt;/p&gt; &lt;p&gt;&lt;span style="font-weight:400"&gt;“Tch! Is it about morality? If so, even if it killed him alone it could protect hundreds, thousands!” She argued.&lt;/span&gt;&lt;/p&gt; &lt;p&gt;&lt;span style="font-weight:400"&gt;“No.” I repeated. “I’m not letting him die, even for that.”&lt;/span&gt;&lt;/p&gt; &lt;p&gt;&lt;span style="font-weight:400"&gt;“Even if I could sweeten the deal?” She added. The parts of her disguise that hadn’t been burned by the holy water shifted to a different form. Her hair color went from blonde to blue, and the outfit turned to some japanese schoolgirl uniform, like in an anime. “I can be any girl you’d want.” Her eyes begin glowing again, that same pink hue from earlier. “It’s all at your fingertips, if you just say-”&lt;/span&gt;&lt;/p&gt; &lt;p&gt;&lt;span style="font-weight:400"&gt;I squirted her again. That was the last of the water in the gun, better not let her notice that.&lt;/span&gt;&lt;/p&gt; &lt;p&gt;&lt;span style="font-weight:400"&gt;Once more Lilianna shrieked in pain, hunching down onto the ground. “DAMN IT ALL!!! WHY??!!!”&lt;/span&gt;&lt;/p&gt; &lt;p&gt;&lt;span style="font-weight:400"&gt;“I’m not interested.” I bluntly answered.&lt;/span&gt;&lt;/p&gt; &lt;p&gt;&lt;span style="font-weight:400"&gt;She huffed, “How?! Again?! Why doesn’t it work?! Every other hunter I’ve met through the centuries has been putty in my hands! It’s like you’re-!” She stopped, eyes wide as she looked at me. “Fuck. Are you gay?”&lt;/span&gt;&lt;/p&gt; &lt;p&gt;&lt;span style="font-weight:400"&gt;I flinched. The accusation came out of nowhere, but it struck. Well, it wasn’t entirely accurate, but it put me off guard to hear it. “Wh-What?”&lt;/span&gt;&lt;/p&gt; &lt;p&gt;&lt;span style="font-weight:400"&gt;“Fucking hell. Of god damn course I run into a homo hunter of all things! That’s what it is!” She continued, eyes suddenly widening as if striking a realization. “Wait, don’t tell me! You’re in love with the boy! Is that why you’re keeping him alive?! Is that why you waited until &lt;/span&gt;&lt;i&gt;&lt;span style="font-weight:400"&gt;now &lt;/span&gt;&lt;/i&gt;&lt;span style="font-weight:400"&gt;of all times to kill me?!”&lt;/span&gt;&lt;/p&gt; &lt;p&gt;&lt;span style="font-weight:400"&gt;I flinched again. “N-No! You’re a threat to everyone! I’d protect all my classmates no matter what!” I paused, “B-Besides, I-I wouldn’t really call it l-love exactly…”&lt;/span&gt;&lt;/p&gt; &lt;p&gt;&lt;span style="font-weight:400"&gt;I felt myself grow a bit embarrassed. “H-He’s just really nice to be around. Just s-special because… he’s my first real friend… B-But I guess it’d be really nice if we had something m-more, if I’m lucky…”&lt;/span&gt;&lt;/p&gt; &lt;p&gt;&lt;span style="font-weight:400"&gt;I wasn’t sure why I was saying all of this. Maybe it was just from having these feelings pent up for so long. “Like spending the day on a d-date, or I dunno, him buying me flowers… Or me laying in his arms…”&lt;/span&gt;&lt;/p&gt; &lt;p&gt;&lt;span style="font-weight:400"&gt;Lilianna seemed on some level confused as I went on, but I wasn’t really paying much mind to what she might be thinking. “We’d spend our days together, moving in, w-watching tv or having dinners together. M-Maybe even getting married, and I could show up in a beautiful white gown a-and he’d tell me I look amazing and w-we’d-!”&lt;/span&gt;&lt;/p&gt; &lt;p&gt;&lt;span style="font-weight:400"&gt;I was interrupted by Lilianna suddenly leaping forward. But before her claws could so much as touch me, I backed away and pressed the remote hidden in my sleeve, activating a sprinkler above us.&lt;/span&gt;&lt;/p&gt; &lt;p&gt;&lt;span style="font-weight:400"&gt;She shrieked in pain the moment the first drop touched her, and it didn’t stop. “S-Sorry, I guess I got a bit carried away there,” I told her, though I got the sense it was hard for her to hear with her entire body practically boiling. I selected this room for a reason. It’s a good thing I’d made sure to mix some holy water into the sprinklers here last week. Had a feeling it’d come in handy once I realised there could have been a hellspawn roaming about.&lt;/span&gt;&lt;/p&gt; &lt;p&gt;&lt;span style="font-weight:400"&gt;Her disguise had completely vanished, her form was practically melting before my very eyes.&lt;/span&gt;&lt;/p&gt; &lt;p&gt;&lt;span style="font-weight:400"&gt;“YOU! CURSE YOU!!! THIS WON’T BE THE EEEENNDDDD!!!!” She belted out in between pained screams, but it didn’t matter. She had no way to avoid the water. By the time the sprinklers were shut off, the only thing left on the floor was a puddle and some personal belongings.&lt;/span&gt;&lt;/p&gt; &lt;p&gt;&lt;span style="font-weight:400"&gt;With the job officially done, I let out a sigh. “Sorry, Soph…”&lt;/span&gt;&lt;/p&gt; &lt;p&gt;&lt;span style="font-weight:400"&gt;Another reason I’d explore sprinklers as an option was to make cleanup easier, as it had pretty much evaporated her entire form. Since it was after school, no one should realise anything had even happened in here at all. Even if someone showed up tomorrow morning, all they’d notice was that some of the things in here were soggy. I’ll leave that part to be an unsolved mystery. Overall, the mission had been cleanly executed.&lt;/span&gt;&lt;/p&gt; &lt;p&gt;&lt;span style="font-weight:400"&gt;“Oh shoot! The phone!” Better grab that before it gets too wet, hope it’s not broken. There weren’t many ways to explain a high school student disappearing overnight. I could get into her social media accounts and make up some excuse about a family emergency forcing her to the other side of the country. Then, when it feels like people have forgotten about her, delete all socials.&lt;/span&gt;&lt;/p&gt; &lt;p&gt;&lt;span style="font-weight:400"&gt;It’s a bit creepy thinking about everything like this, it’s almost as if I just murdered someone. Well, I kinda did, but she was a demon. Letting her roam would’ve meant people dying or going ill. Besides, it’s… my job. My duty. Hunt and slay monsters. Exterminate them to keep people safe.&lt;/span&gt;&lt;/p&gt; &lt;p&gt;&lt;span style="font-weight:400"&gt;I collected the rest of her things, hoping to find time to burn or throw them away, then hurried out of the school building before anyone might notice what I’d been doing here.&lt;/span&gt;&lt;/p&gt; &lt;p&gt; &lt;/p&gt; &lt;hr /&gt; &lt;p&gt; &lt;/p&gt; &lt;p&gt;&lt;i&gt;&lt;span style="font-weight:400"&gt;-7 weeks ago-&lt;/span&gt;&lt;/i&gt;&lt;/p&gt; &lt;p&gt;&lt;i&gt;&lt;span style="font-weight:400"&gt;As the bell rang and the students left for their lunch period, I retreated myself further into my seat.&lt;/span&gt;&lt;/i&gt;&lt;/p&gt; &lt;p&gt;&lt;i&gt;&lt;span style="font-weight:400"&gt;Made myself look small, hunched down on my desk. Ideally, I’d lay low while I executed my mission. It would be simple, and preferably quick. Once everyone is out, I could start searching for any anomalies nearby. &lt;/span&gt;&lt;/i&gt;&lt;/p&gt; &lt;p&gt;&lt;i&gt;&lt;span style="font-weight:400"&gt;They could be anywhere. I’d only just arrived the day before, and all I knew was that supernatural entities were being reported by scouts more commonly from the town of Hallwood. The specific origin, unknown. But that’s why I was here. To figure out what it was we were dealing with.&lt;/span&gt;&lt;/i&gt;&lt;/p&gt; &lt;p&gt;&lt;i&gt;&lt;span style="font-weight:400"&gt;But with my training and education, I felt prepared. I knew how to snuff out the source. &lt;/span&gt;&lt;/i&gt;&lt;/p&gt; &lt;p&gt;&lt;i&gt;&lt;span style="font-weight:400"&gt;Since my seat was all the way in the corner, I went ahead and retrieved the mote of light from my bag, tucked in its little jar. I also brought out a manga volume, Undead Unluck #1. I figured it’d make a convenient cover if I wanted to hide something on my desk, and if I was going to get any book, I might as well be collecting something I might like reading. One benefit of being out on an assignment away from home was how my family wouldn't be here to judge for the things I was buying or reading.&lt;/span&gt;&lt;/i&gt;&lt;/p&gt; &lt;p&gt;&lt;i&gt;&lt;span style="font-weight:400"&gt;The book didn't need to be big or anything. The jars were miniature enough I could fit it almost entirely in my grip, so I only needed to create a small blind spot to leave it on my desk.&lt;/span&gt;&lt;/i&gt;&lt;/p&gt; &lt;p&gt;&lt;i&gt;&lt;span style="font-weight:400"&gt;Motes of light were barely sentient, so their imprisonment was never a problem for anyone. The jars themselves were just a useful container to prevent them from drifting off too far. Even then, the drift was exactly what we wanted them to do.&lt;/span&gt;&lt;/i&gt;&lt;/p&gt; &lt;p&gt;&lt;i&gt;&lt;span style="font-weight:400"&gt;It didn’t work for everything, certainly not a random sasquatch or what have you. But plenty of entities possessed magical qualities to them, and it was magic that they were attracted to. If it drifts in a certain direction in its little jar after a certain amount of time, there was something in the area. Kinda like a really weak compass.&lt;/span&gt;&lt;/i&gt;&lt;/p&gt; &lt;p&gt;&lt;i&gt;&lt;span style="font-weight:400"&gt;I didn’t even need to find the origin of the anomalies specifically, no guarantee it would be the type of phenomenon that attracted a mote anyway. Not as if it had town-wide range either. But so long as it showed any result, I had a lead that I could pursue so I could gather-&lt;/span&gt;&lt;/i&gt;&lt;/p&gt; &lt;p&gt;&lt;i&gt;&lt;span style="font-weight:400"&gt;“Hey, what manga is that?”&lt;/span&gt;&lt;/i&gt;&lt;/p&gt; &lt;p&gt;&lt;i&gt;&lt;span style="font-weight:400"&gt;I was caught off-guard by the sudden question. I made sure not to move the book, so as not to expose the literal floating ball of light I was hiding.&lt;/span&gt;&lt;/i&gt;&lt;/p&gt; &lt;p&gt;&lt;i&gt;&lt;span style="font-weight:400"&gt;It was a boy, probably around my age. He had an earnest quizzical look on his face as he looked at me. Augh, eye contact!&lt;/span&gt;&lt;/i&gt;&lt;/p&gt; &lt;p&gt;&lt;i&gt;&lt;span style="font-weight:400"&gt;“O-Oh! Um, it’s Undead Unluck…” I meekly answered.&lt;/span&gt;&lt;/i&gt;&lt;/p&gt; &lt;p&gt;&lt;i&gt;&lt;span style="font-weight:400"&gt;“Huh, neato! Feel like I’ve heard of that one. Is it good?”&lt;/span&gt;&lt;/i&gt;&lt;/p&gt; &lt;p&gt;&lt;i&gt;&lt;span style="font-weight:400"&gt;I thought everyone was leaving! Don’t these guys have lunch?! Why is someone trying to care about some random kid? I knew what I looked like, barely kept hair and beedy eyes. I’d thought I was unapproachable.&lt;/span&gt;&lt;/i&gt;&lt;/p&gt; &lt;p&gt;&lt;i&gt;&lt;span style="font-weight:400"&gt;Overall it also just felt… weird. The attention. Why did I feel weird? No, it’s just me feeling embarrassed about myself, like usual.&lt;/span&gt;&lt;/i&gt;&lt;/p&gt; &lt;p&gt;&lt;i&gt;&lt;span style="font-weight:400"&gt;“I-It is. At least, I think so.” I answered. That was just my opinion though, I knew I didn’t always like the same stuff as my peers.&lt;/span&gt;&lt;/i&gt;&lt;/p&gt; &lt;p&gt;&lt;i&gt;&lt;span style="font-weight:400"&gt;“Oh cool! Is it okay if I gave it a-?”&lt;/span&gt;&lt;/i&gt;&lt;/p&gt; &lt;p&gt;&lt;i&gt;&lt;span style="font-weight:400"&gt;As he reached his hand out, I instinctively pulled the manga volume back. Crap! Can’t let him see the mote! I’m a failure of a hunter! In my hurry to start locating anomalies I’ve put myself into a risky position already!&lt;/span&gt;&lt;/i&gt;&lt;/p&gt; &lt;p&gt;&lt;i&gt;&lt;span style="font-weight:400"&gt;“I uhh, I-I’m still reading.” I answered as an excuse. “I’m still not done with the volume.”&lt;/span&gt;&lt;/i&gt;&lt;/p&gt; &lt;p&gt;&lt;i&gt;&lt;span style="font-weight:400"&gt;“Oh.” The boy responded, with a disappointed tone. “Ah, sorry then, my bad.”&lt;/span&gt;&lt;/i&gt;&lt;/p&gt; &lt;p&gt;&lt;i&gt;&lt;span style="font-weight:400"&gt;A part of me felt bad for shutting him off like that, but it couldn’t be helped. Besides, I was too busy worrying about my mission to chat about something silly like manga…&lt;/span&gt;&lt;/i&gt;&lt;/p&gt; &lt;p&gt;&lt;i&gt;&lt;span style="font-weight:400"&gt;“Then could you come find me when you’re done?” The boy suddenly asked. “Cover looks interesting! And if you’re so busy reading it, then it’s gotta be good!”&lt;/span&gt;&lt;/i&gt;&lt;/p&gt; &lt;p&gt;&lt;i&gt;&lt;span style="font-weight:400"&gt;He smiled, and I almost felt something well up in my chest. Like… a flutter? More weird stuff.&lt;/span&gt;&lt;/i&gt;&lt;/p&gt; &lt;p&gt;&lt;i&gt;&lt;span style="font-weight:400"&gt;“Um, sure.” I answered. Maybe it was alright to at least humor him. J-Just to get him out of my hair sooner, of course.&lt;/span&gt;&lt;/i&gt;&lt;/p&gt; &lt;p&gt;&lt;i&gt;&lt;span style="font-weight:400"&gt;“Great!” He turned to leave, but suddenly stopped. Turning back, he continued, “Oh, and I’m Noah, by the way. You?”&lt;/span&gt;&lt;/i&gt;&lt;/p&gt; &lt;p&gt;&lt;i&gt;&lt;span style="font-weight:400"&gt;“...Haukur.”&lt;/span&gt;&lt;/i&gt;&lt;/p&gt; &lt;p&gt;&lt;i&gt;&lt;span style="font-weight:400"&gt;“Hawker?”&lt;/span&gt;&lt;/i&gt;&lt;/p&gt; &lt;p&gt;&lt;i&gt;&lt;span style="font-weight:400"&gt;“&lt;/span&gt;&lt;/i&gt;&lt;span style="font-weight:400"&gt;Haukur&lt;/span&gt;&lt;i&gt;&lt;span style="font-weight:400"&gt;.”&lt;/span&gt;&lt;/i&gt;&lt;/p&gt; &lt;p&gt;&lt;i&gt;&lt;span style="font-weight:400"&gt;“Hawker.”&lt;/span&gt;&lt;/i&gt;&lt;/p&gt; &lt;p&gt;&lt;i&gt;&lt;span style="font-weight:400"&gt;“No, it’s-!” I was about to repeat, but I stopped myself. No, obviously some things are harder to pronounce than others. It’s not like I was too fond of my name anyway. “...Actually, feel free to just call me whatever. It’s Icelandic, I know it’s hard to pronounce.”&lt;/span&gt;&lt;/i&gt;&lt;/p&gt; &lt;p&gt;&lt;i&gt;&lt;span style="font-weight:400"&gt;“Ohh, gotcha.” Noah replied. “Then I’ll just call you Hawk, yeah?”&lt;/span&gt;&lt;/i&gt;&lt;/p&gt; &lt;p&gt;&lt;i&gt;&lt;span style="font-weight:400"&gt;He smiled again, and like before, I felt that weird sensation in my chest.&lt;/span&gt;&lt;/i&gt;&lt;/p&gt; &lt;p&gt;&lt;i&gt;&lt;span style="font-weight:400"&gt;“...Huh?”&lt;/span&gt;&lt;/i&gt;&lt;/p&gt; &lt;p&gt;&lt;i&gt;&lt;span style="font-weight:400"&gt;“You know, like the bird!” He explained. “Feels like the type of name someone in an anime might have. It’s badass! Hawks are pretty fierce!”&lt;/span&gt;&lt;/i&gt;&lt;/p&gt; &lt;p&gt;&lt;i&gt;&lt;span style="font-weight:400"&gt;He felt weirdly excited explaining that. With no reason to object, I answered, “Um, sure.”&lt;/span&gt;&lt;/i&gt;&lt;/p&gt; &lt;p&gt;&lt;i&gt;&lt;span style="font-weight:400"&gt;“Then I’ll catch ya later, Hawk!” He greeted, before finally heading off.&lt;/span&gt;&lt;/i&gt;&lt;/p&gt; &lt;p&gt;&lt;i&gt;&lt;span style="font-weight:400"&gt;I sighed, relieved in more ways than one, now that he was finally getting out of my hair. I was officially alone in the classroom now, every other student long gone. So I could safely wait and see if the mote-&lt;/span&gt;&lt;/i&gt;&lt;/p&gt; &lt;p&gt;&lt;i&gt;&lt;span style="font-weight:400"&gt;As I looked down at my desk, I saw it pushing against its jar.&lt;/span&gt;&lt;/i&gt;&lt;/p&gt; &lt;p&gt;&lt;i&gt;&lt;span style="font-weight:400"&gt;So much that it was practically squeezing against it. Hell, I could swear it was slightly &lt;/span&gt;&lt;/i&gt;&lt;span style="font-weight:400"&gt;budging &lt;/span&gt;&lt;i&gt;&lt;span style="font-weight:400"&gt;it. &lt;/span&gt;&lt;/i&gt;&lt;/p&gt; &lt;p&gt;&lt;i&gt;&lt;span style="font-weight:400"&gt;I’d never seen it do that before. Was it supposed to do that? &lt;/span&gt;&lt;/i&gt;&lt;/p&gt; &lt;p&gt;&lt;i&gt;&lt;span style="font-weight:400"&gt;What’s more, it slid across the side, going from pushing against one corner to another. The direction of… the classroom door. &lt;/span&gt;&lt;/i&gt;&lt;/p&gt; &lt;p&gt;&lt;i&gt;&lt;span style="font-weight:400"&gt;Quickly, I stood up and ran to the door, holding the tiny jar in my palm.&lt;/span&gt;&lt;/i&gt;&lt;/p&gt; &lt;p&gt;&lt;i&gt;&lt;span style="font-weight:400"&gt;I exited the room, finding myself in the middle of the hallway.&lt;/span&gt;&lt;/i&gt;&lt;/p&gt; &lt;p&gt;&lt;i&gt;&lt;span style="font-weight:400"&gt;I pulled the jarred mote back up, holding it so that I was keeping it still and at balance. It took no time to drift and push straight into the jar again. &lt;/span&gt;&lt;/i&gt;&lt;/p&gt; &lt;p&gt;&lt;i&gt;&lt;span style="font-weight:400"&gt;And it was pointed… directly down the hallway.&lt;/span&gt;&lt;/i&gt;&lt;/p&gt; &lt;p&gt;&lt;i&gt;&lt;span style="font-weight:400"&gt;At the end, I saw Noah, still walking along.&lt;/span&gt;&lt;/i&gt;&lt;/p&gt; &lt;p&gt;&lt;i&gt;&lt;span style="font-weight:400"&gt;He turned a corner to the left, presumably heading towards lunch.&lt;/span&gt;&lt;/i&gt;&lt;/p&gt; &lt;p&gt;&lt;i&gt;&lt;span style="font-weight:400"&gt;As he did so, the mote of light slid a few degrees left.&lt;/span&gt;&lt;/i&gt;&lt;/p&gt; &lt;p&gt;&lt;i&gt;&lt;span style="font-weight:400"&gt;My heartbeat quickened. Because the implication was clear. This was a way stronger reaction than expected. Had I found it already? But the reaction also implied that whatever was being detected in that direction was nearby, so… N-No, couldn’t be…&lt;/span&gt;&lt;/i&gt;&lt;/p&gt; &lt;p&gt;&lt;i&gt;&lt;span style="font-weight:400"&gt;My heart only raced more, as I thought back to him. It wasn’t just the social awkwardness of the conversation, I still felt the same weirdness just imagining having to talk to him again. Of him giving me attention, or that smile. &lt;/span&gt;&lt;/i&gt;&lt;/p&gt; &lt;p&gt;&lt;i&gt;&lt;span style="font-weight:400"&gt;I-It couldn’t be that I was…&lt;/span&gt;&lt;/i&gt;&lt;/p&gt; &lt;p&gt;&lt;i&gt;&lt;span style="font-weight:400"&gt;…No, that’d be silly.&lt;/span&gt;&lt;/i&gt;&lt;/p&gt; &lt;p&gt;&lt;i&gt;&lt;span style="font-weight:400"&gt;Though it probably wouldn’t hurt to talk to him again later. F-For investigative purposes…&lt;/span&gt;&lt;/i&gt;&lt;/p&gt; &lt;p&gt; &lt;/p&gt; &lt;hr /&gt; &lt;p&gt; &lt;/p&gt; &lt;p&gt;-Present Day-&lt;/p&gt; &lt;p&gt;&lt;span style="font-weight:400"&gt;I closed the door to my small personal apartment, breathing a sigh of relief. I threw Lilianna’s things off to the side, then exhaustedly plopped down onto my bed. It’s not like today had been difficult, it just felt right to take a breather after eliminating a hellspawn. Those would be one of the tougher ones, in some way I should be proud I managed that so efficiently. It’s a good day’s work, so I deserved to feel a bit tired. I would have to write that social media post later tonight too, before everyone started asking questions at school tomorrow.&lt;/span&gt;&lt;/p&gt; &lt;p&gt;&lt;span style="font-weight:400"&gt;I eventually sat back up, about to collect her phone, when I heard a knock on my window.&lt;/span&gt;&lt;/p&gt; &lt;p&gt;&lt;span style="font-weight:400"&gt;It was a raven. It turned its head to get a better look at me with each eye. A white piece of paper was bound by its leg as well. “Shit.”&lt;/span&gt;&lt;/p&gt; &lt;p&gt;&lt;span style="font-weight:400"&gt;I opened the window to let it in. I then took out some blueberries from my fridge and put it in a bowl for the little guy. It happily stood in place, pecking on them as I tied loose the note.&lt;/span&gt;&lt;/p&gt; &lt;p&gt;&lt;span style="font-weight:400"&gt;I gulped, unravelling it to read. As expected, a handwritten letter from home, in my native Icelandic. &lt;/span&gt;&lt;/p&gt; &lt;p&gt; &lt;/p&gt; &lt;p style="padding-left:120px"&gt;&lt;i&gt;&lt;span style="font-weight:400"&gt;Addressed to: Haukur.&lt;/span&gt;&lt;/i&gt;&lt;/p&gt; &lt;p style="padding-left:40px;text-align:justify"&gt;&lt;i&gt;&lt;span style="font-weight:400"&gt;As of writing, it has been one month since you landed in America, and arrived in the town of Hallwood. As we have not heard back yet, we would like a status report on how you fare in locating the anomaly you were tasked with. As this is your first assignment for the clan, it would not be strange to ask for assistance in guiding you from someone with more experience. Let us know if you would like the aid. If this continues, please write to us weekly of your progress. We have also loaned you Ásgeir for ease of access to a raven.&lt;/span&gt;&lt;/i&gt;&lt;/p&gt; &lt;p&gt; &lt;/p&gt; &lt;p&gt;&lt;span style="font-weight:400"&gt;I looked back at the raven, still pecking on the last few berries. I assumed that had to be Ásgeir then. Convenient, although…&lt;/span&gt;&lt;/p&gt; &lt;p&gt;&lt;span style="font-weight:400"&gt;What the hell was I gonna write back?! Of course they’d check in on me! I mean, I had the blueberries ready specifically in case one of our ravens came knocking, the letter was inevitable. But they wanted someone to come in and help? Or for me to explain what I was doing?&lt;/span&gt;&lt;/p&gt; &lt;p&gt;&lt;span style="font-weight:400"&gt;They thought it’d be natural for someone as young as me to take a bit longer than expected with my assignment. But really, it had barely taken me more than a day to be confident. &lt;/span&gt;&lt;/p&gt; &lt;p&gt;&lt;span style="font-weight:400"&gt;I just didn’t know how they’d respond if I told them it was a &lt;/span&gt;&lt;i&gt;&lt;span style="font-weight:400"&gt;person.&lt;/span&gt;&lt;/i&gt;&lt;span style="font-weight:400"&gt; Not some object or a monster. But some teenage boy who just wanted to live his life. Protocol usually didn’t demand we kill humans, at least not if they didn’t pose &lt;/span&gt;&lt;i&gt;&lt;span style="font-weight:400"&gt;direct &lt;/span&gt;&lt;/i&gt;&lt;span style="font-weight:400"&gt;harm to others. But I figured there would h-have to be some extreme measures, especially when the reading from him was just &lt;em&gt;that&lt;/em&gt; strong. Move him into isolation, keep him in a facility, or what have you. They'd argue his presence attracts danger to everyone around him.&lt;/span&gt;&lt;/p&gt; &lt;p&gt;&lt;span style="font-weight:400"&gt;As far as I knew, there was no way to fix his condition either. Heck, though it’s not like I knew anything about such a condition myself! In all my years training, no one had ever taught me about this! There was a chance the succubus idea would work, draining his energy, but even in the best case it might put him close to death.&lt;/span&gt;&lt;/p&gt; &lt;p&gt;&lt;span style="font-weight:400"&gt;I’d have to tell them something, but I also wouldn’t want some other hunter showing up and making the decision for me when they found out. &lt;/span&gt;&lt;/p&gt; &lt;p&gt;&lt;span style="font-weight:400"&gt;I sat back down on my bed, and lied down. I curled up into a little ball. This situation sucked. I didn’t want to ruin Noah’s life. He didn’t even have a clue about any of this.&lt;/span&gt;&lt;/p&gt; &lt;p&gt;&lt;span style="font-weight:400"&gt;It’s not like I thought I actually had a chance with him. I can’t be a girl for him. Not until way way later in my life, by which point we'll be far apart. There’s also the whole bit about me being an agent of a secret monster hunting clan and all.&lt;/span&gt;&lt;/p&gt; &lt;p&gt;&lt;span style="font-weight:400"&gt;But that part didn’t really matter in this case. Regardless of whether I was a girl or not or if he liked me, I… wanted to let him be happy.&lt;/span&gt;&lt;/p&gt; &lt;p&gt;&lt;span style="font-weight:400"&gt;And being with everyone also made &lt;/span&gt;&lt;i&gt;&lt;span style="font-weight:400"&gt;me&lt;/span&gt;&lt;/i&gt;&lt;span style="font-weight:400"&gt; happy. Lord knows my cousins and relatives back at home rarely paid me any mind, and the same went for the parts of actual normal schooling I had in between the training. I actually liked having friends for once.&lt;/span&gt;&lt;/p&gt; &lt;p&gt;&lt;span style="font-weight:400"&gt;“Caw!”&lt;/span&gt;&lt;/p&gt; &lt;p&gt;&lt;span style="font-weight:400"&gt;Ásgeir flapped his wings and flew over to the bed. He peered his eyes at me, tilting his head to the side and back like he was curious about me. I let out a weak smile. “Want some more blueberries? Heh, definitely better than the normal feed you get back home.”&lt;/span&gt;&lt;/p&gt; &lt;p&gt;&lt;span style="font-weight:400"&gt;I stood back up, and got to work. My day wasn’t quite over. &lt;/span&gt;&lt;/p&gt; &lt;p&gt;&lt;span style="font-weight:400"&gt;I’ll send them a basic, yet somewhat truthful report back home. If I can convince them I’m just busy still taking care of the monsters in the area, then hopefully it’s not too much of an issue that I haven’t found the source just yet. Just keep doing things as I’ve been doing.&lt;/span&gt;&lt;/p&gt; &lt;p&gt;Keep doing things as I've been doing...&lt;/p&gt; &lt;p&gt;&lt;span style="font-weight:400"&gt;…You know, come to think of it though. Lilianna &lt;/span&gt;&lt;i&gt;&lt;span style="font-weight:400"&gt;did&lt;/span&gt;&lt;/i&gt;&lt;span style="font-weight:400"&gt; have some nice hips. Wonder if Noah would pay more attention to me like that if I had a pair of those…&lt;/span&gt;&lt;/p&gt; &lt;p&gt; &lt;/p&gt; &lt;div class="wi_authornotes"&gt; &lt;div&gt; &lt;div class="p-avatar-wrap"&gt;&lt;a class="avatar has-link" href="/profile/154863/ternunfettered/"&gt;&lt;img id="acc_ava_change profile" alt="" src="https://cdn.scribblehub.com/avatar/s/38/ava_154863_1712054303.jpg"&gt;&lt;/a&gt;&lt;/div&gt; &lt;p&gt;&lt;span class="an_username"&gt;&lt;a href="/profile/154863/ternunfettered/"&gt;TernUnfettered&lt;/a&gt;&lt;/span&gt;&lt;/div&gt; &lt;div style="clear: both;"&gt;&lt;/div&gt; &lt;div class="wi_authornotes_body"&gt;  Surprise! New series!&lt;/p&gt; &lt;p&gt;I know, and yes, I still want to finish Luftdatter. But motivation to write is wrecking me and I still want to write so I'm choosing to focus on another idea that I'm actually invested in creating. This is an episodic story, so if releases end up sparse, then it won't break the reading experience. I hope readers are as into this premise as I am. It has led to a lot of brainblasts this year that still leaves plenty of room for writing ingenuinity to happen as I slowly make my way through it. I already have one more chapter ready, and I'm well on my way on working on the third and fourth chapters. As these chapters are all long and, again, episodic, releases will be spread out more even when I have stuff ready in advance. But that'll be it from me here.&lt;/p&gt; &lt;p&gt;Join us next time, when Hawk borrows a pen from her crush!&lt;/p&gt;&lt;/div&gt; &lt;/p&gt;&lt;/div&gt;&lt;/p&gt; &lt;/div&gt;</description>
