      <title>Reborn In Moonlight</title>
      <author> Trinidia </author>
      <link>https://www.scribblehub.com/series/1764124/reborn-in-moonlight/</link>
      <comments>https://www.scribblehub.com/read/1764124-reborn-in-moonlight/chapter/1764128/#comments</comments>
      <guid isPermaLink="false">e8a65f21cf425ed22f7c6cc9a48929965dc37e54</guid>
      <pubDate>Sat, 23 Aug 2025 00:00:00 +0000</pubDate>
      <description>&lt;div class="wi_fic_desc" property="description"&gt;&lt;p&gt;Sometimes bad things happens to good people. Sometimes those bad things are not the end but a new beginning. Once the sun champion returned from defeating the evil dragon lord only to be betrayed by one closest to her. Now the moon has decided she deserves a second change to live life in the way she had secretly desired.&lt;/p&gt; &lt;/div&gt;&lt;hr&gt;&lt;h3&gt;&lt;a href="https://www.scribblehub.com/read/1764124-reborn-in-moonlight/chapter/1764128/"&gt;&lt;div class="chapter-title"&gt;Chapter 1: So This Is It&lt;/div&gt;&lt;/a&gt;&lt;/h3&gt;&lt;div class="chp_raw" id="chp_raw"&gt;&lt;p&gt;&lt;span style="font-weight:400"&gt;“Take a deep breath, hold it, then let it out through your nose.” The melodic clop of the horses' hooves were a great way to count. To find the right amount of time to hold the breath in, and then how long it took to let it out.&lt;/span&gt;&lt;/p&gt; &lt;p&gt;&lt;span style="font-weight:400"&gt;“You alright, Cardamom?” Sarah said, riding her horse up to his right.&lt;/span&gt;&lt;/p&gt; &lt;p&gt;&lt;span style="font-weight:400"&gt;Cardamom turned and smiled at his dwelf companion. “I’m alright.” He took another deep breath and turned back to the approaching gate. He could already hear the cheering. “Crowds are just hard.”&lt;/span&gt;&lt;/p&gt; &lt;p&gt;&lt;span style="font-weight:400"&gt;“Well, I’m sorry, but you’re going to have to get used to it as hero and king.” Sarah had been by his side the longest of all their little party. From before the dawn of this quest of theirs even rose. She wasn’t just here because of their quest either. She was here for more than all this. She was here for him. &lt;/span&gt;&lt;/p&gt; &lt;p&gt;&lt;span style="font-weight:400"&gt;“Don’t remind me,” he said playfully. “If I knew this is what being Sun Champion would lead to, I would have turned to the moon instead.” He couldn’t help but laugh a little. He had known full well what becoming the champion of the sun god meant. He knew he was giving up his life of peace and comfort for a greater purpose. What else could he do though? He was the prince of the Hale Kingdom, and his people needed a champion. No. The people of this world needed a champion. Though many others were trying to become champion he still threw his hat into the ring just in case it would be him. He still wasn’t sure whether it was good luck or misfortune that he was chosen.&lt;/span&gt;&lt;/p&gt; &lt;p&gt;&lt;span style="font-weight:400"&gt;“Then it is good you had no true choice,” Bofoir, dwarven prince of the Donnadwell Empire, called from behind him. “Well, good for us!” Bofoir had only joined the party after Cardamom beat him in a fight of honor. The dwarf’s hammer had broken eight of his ribs before he even landed a hit on the prince. Really Cardamom hadn’t won the fight itself as Bofoir had two hundred years more fighting experience than him, but every time he was knocked down by that blasted hammer he got back up again. That had earned him Bofoir’s respect and won the honor of the fight.&lt;/span&gt;&lt;/p&gt; &lt;p&gt;&lt;span style="font-weight:400"&gt;“Good for all people of the world, Bofoir. That includes Cardamom himself too,” Lady Lyari, half elf ambassador of the Forgotten Woods, said clearly trying to lighten Cardamom’s growing anxiety. Always the healer she was, of both body and mind. Also healer of ribs specifically in Cardamom’s case. “He has earned a life of rest and the immortal love of his people. Good things come to those who do good deeds.”&lt;/span&gt;&lt;/p&gt; &lt;p&gt;&lt;span style="font-weight:400"&gt;“Well, I’m fucked then,” Sazel, the other human besides cardamom said. It was hard to determine from his quiet voice if he was serious or playful. Maybe it was both. Sazel had not come to the party from good origins. All he would say was that he was a street rat that just happened to be in the wrong place at the wrong time. That wrong time being trying to steal from the party, only to be roped into joining them. Cardamom still wasn’t sure how they managed that, but they had needed someone who was light on their feet and deft of hand.&lt;/span&gt;&lt;/p&gt; &lt;p&gt;&lt;span style="font-weight:400"&gt;“Don’t say that,” Sarah called out to him. “Sure, we’ve all done some pretty fuck up shit on this journey, but the good out weights the bad.” She smiled at Sazel. The kind of smile Cardamom adored when it was pointed at him. “If not, then take solace in that we are all royally fucked.”&lt;/span&gt;&lt;/p&gt; &lt;p&gt;&lt;span style="font-weight:400"&gt;“Well, Sarah, if Cardamom wants to get fucked all he has to do is ask yo—” Bofoir’s helmet rang out with the dull thunk of a stale piece of bread hitting him with enough force to nearly topple him over. Said stale bread had been a running joke for the party as they were all convinced you could kill a man with it. Sarah sure as well did her damnedest by throwing it at the dwarf.&lt;/span&gt;&lt;/p&gt; &lt;p&gt;&lt;span style="font-weight:400"&gt;“Shut it, Bofoir!” Sarah gave a glance back over to Cardamom. When their eyes met both of them felt their faces warm up. Sarah was the first to look away.&lt;/span&gt;&lt;/p&gt; &lt;p&gt;&lt;span style="font-weight:400"&gt;It was well known by this point that the both of them had strong feelings for one another. Honestly strong enough to be called love at this point. They had fought their hardest when protecting the other. They were never known to be too far apart, and whenever the party had to split it was always the pair of them that went off together. They both knew they loved each other, and while that should have made them both happy, it only hurt Cardamom more because he was the reason they weren’t together. There was another woman who was sadly more important to him right now. One who he would be with soon.&lt;/span&gt;&lt;/p&gt; &lt;p&gt;&lt;span style="font-weight:400"&gt;Finally the party reached the gates. Guards cheered at them as they opened the gates for them. Then the true cheering of the crowd within roared to life. It was so loud, and Cardamom wasn’t prepared for it. Sazel also clearly wasn’t prepared. The rest of the party were all smiles and waves already. Putting on a smile himself and praying to the sun that this will be over soon, he reached his right arm up to wave. It only felt like he was reaching up though, for there was no longer a right arm to wave.&lt;/span&gt;&lt;/p&gt; &lt;p&gt;&lt;span style="font-weight:400"&gt;The battle with the dragon lord had been grueling. Though it was only over in mere minutes it had felt like an eternity. All of them had put their all into the fight and it wasn’t enough. They tried and tried, but one by one they all fell. Cardamom stood alone as the rest of his party lay around him on death’s door. His sword shattered and nothing but a handle in his hand. &lt;/span&gt;&lt;/p&gt; &lt;p&gt;&lt;span style="font-weight:400"&gt;The dragon lord mocked him. Mocked all of his friends and stood proudly without a scratch. Cardamom fought on only with his fists but they did so little to the dragon in man’s form. Too soon he was tired and barely able to stand. That was what he wanted though. He wanted to look weak and tired. He wanted the dragon lord to be confident in his own victory. Cardamom wanted him to not be afraid of a punch.&lt;/span&gt;&lt;/p&gt; &lt;p&gt;&lt;span style="font-weight:400"&gt;As the dragon lord’s victory looked assured and he laughed at the weak human that stood before him, Cardamom channeled all the power the sun god had granted him into one single point. He not only used all the power he had, but opened himself up to the full power of the sun itself. The dragon only thought it was another weak punch. He didn’t think the human was capable of anything more than a simple weak harmless punch. In his hubris, he didn’t even attempt to avoid the incoming hit. That was how the reign of the dragon lord ended. One single punch.&lt;/span&gt;&lt;/p&gt; &lt;p&gt;&lt;span style="font-weight:400"&gt;A little unsure of letting go of the reins, Cardamom reached up with his left arm and waved to the people of his kingdom. Waved to the people he saved. Waved to the people he was willing to give his everything for.&lt;/span&gt;&lt;/p&gt; &lt;p&gt;&lt;span style="font-weight:400"&gt;~~~&lt;/span&gt;&lt;/p&gt; &lt;p&gt;&lt;span style="font-weight:400"&gt;“And then I said, what did you think I was, a dwarf?” Bofoir belted out laughing at his own story. “I have never seen an elf more fucking confused than that!” The rest of the tabled all laughed, though none as hard as Bofoir.&lt;/span&gt;&lt;/p&gt; &lt;p&gt;&lt;span style="font-weight:400"&gt;After a long parade through the capital and all the way to the castle, the party had been whisked away into the pleasures of warm baths and clean clothes. Now they all sat at a feast held in their honor. There was so much food and drink, that no one wasn’t walking home stuffed and drunk.&lt;/span&gt;&lt;/p&gt; &lt;p&gt;&lt;span style="font-weight:400"&gt;“Gods, I do not envy your tales brother,” Thyme, Cardamoms young brother, jested.&lt;/span&gt;&lt;/p&gt; &lt;p&gt;&lt;span style="font-weight:400"&gt;“What? No wish to go out and see how the real world is?” Cardamom lifted his new mug of ale to his face, but stopped. There was a str—&lt;/span&gt;&lt;/p&gt; &lt;p&gt;&lt;span style="font-weight:400"&gt;“Come on Thyme,” Sarah said from Cardamom’s right. “You have to get out and live a little! Go out and get fucked like you’ve never been fucked before!” Sarah’s face was red and she was clearly enjoying the ale far too much. Who was to stop her though? They had all earned a night of drinking themselves silly.&lt;/span&gt;&lt;/p&gt; &lt;p&gt;&lt;span style="font-weight:400"&gt;“Who says I don’t fuck? Just because I prefer books and spells to steel and stale bread doesn’t mean I don’t get around.”&lt;/span&gt;&lt;/p&gt; &lt;p&gt;&lt;span style="font-weight:400"&gt;“Maybe Sazel has a shot then—” For the second time that day Bofoir was struck in the head by a piece of bread. This time by Cardamom. “Oy! How are you so good at aiming? I thought you were right handed.”&lt;/span&gt;&lt;/p&gt; &lt;p&gt;&lt;span style="font-weight:400"&gt;“I think he’s left-handed when hes…” Lyari started out, clearly drunk herself, but trailed off as she tried to clearly hold in the ale trying to make its way back out of her. For some reason the few times she got drunk, she turned into a bigger pervert than Bofoir.&lt;/span&gt;&lt;/p&gt; &lt;p&gt;&lt;span style="font-weight:400"&gt;“I think you might have had enough,” Sazel said, already reaching up to hold Lyari’s hair back in case she lost the battle she was clearly fighting. Sazel’s face was still tomato red thanks to Bofoir’s words. He wouldn’t look anyone in the eyes, not that he would do that normally. It was also a not so secret secret that Sazel clearly had a crush on Thyme. Cardamom didn’t think it was well deserved though. Though he loved his brother, his brother had tendencies to see people only for their usages and not for who they were.&lt;/span&gt;&lt;/p&gt; &lt;p&gt;&lt;span style="font-weight:400"&gt;“I guess it’s about time then,” Cardamom said with a sigh. This was the part he had been dreading about tonight, but also the part he needed the most. Standing up from his chair at the head of the table, he raised his mug high and called out to the room, “Tonight we feast for we have done what many thought impossible.” The voices and chatter died down as all eyes focused on him. “Together we defeated those who would have seen an end to our peaceful way of life. We defeated the dragon lord and his armies.” His audience cheered. “The times of plenty will be returning to not just this kingdom, but to all places of the world, for we have fostered new and grand alliances with many other peoples.” He nodded to Bofoir and Lyari. “These struggles haven’t made us weaker, but stronger! We have shown the world that we stand stronger and better together, so to that I say cheers!” The crowd roared and everyone chugged away at ale or wine, including Cardamom. As he pulled his mug away from his face the smile he had been putting on left.&lt;/span&gt;&lt;/p&gt; &lt;p&gt;&lt;span style="font-weight:400"&gt;“I know, I have done much for the kingdom. I have earned my place as hero and king.” Everyone looked at him funny, but he ignored it and gestured for Thyme to stand up next to him. When his brother did he spoke again. “While I have been away fighting for everyone, my brother has stood firm as ruler of the Hale. He has taken care of all of you, and for that he must be thanked.” The cheers grew again, but not nearly as much as they had for him. Then he turned to Thyme directly. “This is hard to hear, I am sure, but there is something… someone grander that calls my name. To follow my own happiness, I must go to her.” Everyone turned to look at Sarah, but not him. It wasn’t her and that broke his heart. &lt;/span&gt;&lt;/p&gt; &lt;p&gt;&lt;span style="font-weight:400"&gt;“The woman in the locket?” Bofoir asked quietly, turning back to Cardamom.&lt;/span&gt;&lt;/p&gt; &lt;p&gt;&lt;span style="font-weight:400"&gt;That took him by surprise. He had thought he was stealthy about his glances into the locket he kept hidden around his neck. But by the way everyone looked, most of all Sarah, it was clear that all of them knew about it. It almost made him cry.&lt;/span&gt;&lt;/p&gt; &lt;p&gt;&lt;span style="font-weight:400"&gt;On their journey a seer they met along the way had shown each of them something. Something private for each of them, and to Cardamom, she had shown him this woman. She was everything he had ever wanted. She was beautiful and lovely and Cardamom had longed for her the second her image came into his mind. She was the woman he saw before he went to sleep each night. She was the woman he dreamed about each night. She was the woman that filled his mind during the day. He had drawn an image of her and put in a locket for himself to look at when no one was around. Evidently others had clearly seen.&lt;/span&gt;&lt;/p&gt; &lt;p&gt;&lt;span style="font-weight:400"&gt;Cardamom nodded solemnly. “Yes. This is something I must do alone…” Sarah wasn’t looking at him anymore and that hurt worst of all. “I… I don’t think I will ever be returning.” Now there were murmurs in the crowd and Sarah did finally look at him again, with tears in her eyes. Cardamom swallowed back tears of his own. Then he put back on that smile “So, Thyme, I leave the kingdom in your capable hands. From this day forward you are king of Hale. All hail the king!” Cheers rose up, but they were all so full of confusion. Still no one missed a chance to take another drink, including him. He really needed it.&lt;/span&gt;&lt;/p&gt; &lt;p&gt;&lt;span style="font-weight:400"&gt;The smile on Thyme’s face was big, but Cardamom could see a little something in his eyes. Regret maybe? Then Thymes eyes gave a quick glance down at the ale in Cardamom’s hand, after his eyes darted to a woman he hadn’t met yet, then moved to Sazel and finally back up to Cardamom. It happened so fast, Cardamom almost didn’t catch it, but he did. The world seemed to pause as his mind worked through all of it. Realization eventually came over Cardamom, even if it was hard to accept. Then it wasn’t hard to accept. His brother had always wished to rule even if he never blatantly admitted it. Sorrow and pain filled Cardamom’s heart, but he didn’t let it show.&lt;/span&gt;&lt;/p&gt; &lt;p&gt;&lt;span style="font-weight:400"&gt;“Take care of the kingdom, Thyme. They need a strong and kind ruler.” He set his mug down and then patted his brother on the back. Then he whispered, “Take care of it, or I’ll come back and haunt you.”&lt;/span&gt;&lt;/p&gt; &lt;p&gt;&lt;span style="font-weight:400"&gt;“I-I-I’m sor—”&lt;/span&gt;&lt;/p&gt; &lt;p&gt;&lt;span style="font-weight:400"&gt;Cardamom cut off his brother. “Do as I say.” Then he turned away from the man who had killed him, and strode over to Sazel as the talking in the room slowly picked back up to an almost normal level. He leant down and whispered quietly, “Cure?” Sazel shook his head. He had suspected as much. Sarah had said they’d done some fucked up things in their journey, and one of those had sadly been poisoning a group of dragon cultists. He knew the poison used then was the same as now. Something that had no cure. All of Cardamom’s hopes for a happy life were crushed. “How long?”&lt;/span&gt;&lt;/p&gt; &lt;p&gt;&lt;span style="font-weight:400"&gt;“Fifteen minutes.”&lt;/span&gt;&lt;/p&gt; &lt;p&gt;&lt;span style="font-weight:400"&gt;He nodded. “You deserve better than him.” Before Sazel could respond he stood back up, a smile beaming on his face to show the world there was nothing wrong. “Right.” All the party all turned to him. “I’m going to step outside for some air.” With that he started walking away.&lt;/span&gt;&lt;/p&gt; &lt;p&gt;&lt;span style="font-weight:400"&gt;“I’ll come with you,” Sarah said, standing up and rushing to him. &lt;/span&gt;&lt;/p&gt; &lt;p&gt;&lt;span style="font-weight:400"&gt;“No,” he said firmly. He hated the worry in her eyes. “I just need a little while to myself.” Then he did something he had never done before. He reached up and cupped her cheek. This would be the last time he ever touched her, and he tried to treasure every second of it. He studied her curly red hair, and her emerald eyes. They were beautiful. “When I get back we can talk as much as you want, alright?”&lt;/span&gt;&lt;/p&gt; &lt;p&gt;&lt;span style="font-weight:400"&gt;She was so clearly stunned and confused. “B-but I w—”&lt;/span&gt;&lt;/p&gt; &lt;p&gt;&lt;span style="font-weight:400"&gt;“Please, I just want to be by myself for a little bit. I promise we’ll talk for as long as you want.”&lt;/span&gt;&lt;/p&gt; &lt;p&gt;&lt;span style="font-weight:400"&gt;“O-okay.”&lt;/span&gt;&lt;/p&gt; &lt;p&gt;&lt;span style="font-weight:400"&gt;He pulled his hand away from her face, and internally wept. That would be the last time he ever touched another person. “I’ll see you in a little bit.” He gave her one last big smile and turned away before she could see him cry.&lt;/span&gt;&lt;/p&gt; &lt;p&gt;&lt;span style="font-weight:400"&gt;Within five minutes Cardamom was alone on a secluded garden balcony. This had always been his favorite spot to escape to as a child, and it seemed a little fitting it was where he would meet his end. Slowly he sat himself down in one of the chairs and looked out at the night sky. The moon was full and bright. Its beauty was unparalleled. “So, this is it…” Tears were brimming in Cardamom’s eyes as he pulled the locket from his neck. With a shaky and clumsy single hand he opened it and looked at the woman within.&lt;/span&gt;&lt;/p&gt; &lt;p&gt;&lt;span style="font-weight:400"&gt;“I’m sorry… I’m so sorry.” Cardamom was sobbing now. “I’m so sorry I never got to be you.” The seer had shown Cardamom not the woman he longed for, but the woman she could be. The woman she was meant to be. The seer had told Cardamom she could help her become who she truly was inside. She could have done it then and there, but Cardamom would have had to give up her quest to save the world. So she decided to stay the man people thought her to be. Be the champion of the sun and save everyone from the dragon lord’s rule. The seer had told her when everything was done, she could come back and she would still help her. &lt;/span&gt;&lt;/p&gt; &lt;p&gt;&lt;span style="font-weight:400"&gt;Cardamom looked back to the sky and sobbed. All she had wanted was to know peace and comfort in her own body. To feel whole and right, and she had worked so gods damn hard to make sure everyone else was taken care of before herself. So that she would have no obligations left but to look after herself. Now she would never get the chance. She would never get to feel right and whole. She’d never get to be who she was always meant to be.&lt;/span&gt;&lt;/p&gt; &lt;p&gt;&lt;span style="font-weight:400"&gt;She’d never get to see Sarah’s smile again…&lt;/span&gt;&lt;/p&gt; &lt;p&gt;&lt;span style="font-weight:400"&gt;There she sat and wept till the darkness of death started to creep in. Her vision quickly tunneled as she felt her heart slow down. Her limbs became heavy. With the last bit of effort she could muster, she looked back up to the dazzling moon.&lt;/span&gt;&lt;/p&gt; &lt;p&gt;&lt;span style="font-weight:400"&gt;“I wish… I could have been half as beautiful as you…” Then life left her.&lt;/span&gt;&lt;/p&gt; &lt;p&gt; &lt;/p&gt; &lt;div class="wi_authornotes"&gt; &lt;div&gt; &lt;div class="p-avatar-wrap"&gt;&lt;a class="avatar has-link" href="/profile/27651/trinidia/"&gt;&lt;img id="acc_ava_change profile" alt="" src="https://cdn.scribblehub.com/avatar/s/6/ava_27651_1724192049.jpg"&gt;&lt;/a&gt;&lt;/div&gt; &lt;p&gt;&lt;span class="an_username"&gt;&lt;a href="/profile/27651/trinidia/"&gt;Trinidia&lt;/a&gt;&lt;/span&gt;&lt;/div&gt; &lt;div style="clear: both;"&gt;&lt;/div&gt; &lt;div class="wi_authornotes_body"&gt; This is a little series I started a good while ago. I haven't done much with it since, but I though you guys would like this while I take a break from Vixen's Mistress.&lt;/div&gt; &lt;/p&gt;&lt;/div&gt;&lt;/p&gt; &lt;/div&gt;</description>
