      <description>&lt;div class="wi_fic_desc" property="description"&gt;&lt;p&gt;A gloomy fairy tale, of a prince trapped by duty and expectation. The principality veers towards civil war, when the last ruler is about to die without a male heir. The widow makes a fateful decision, and through sorcery her daughter is born in the body of a boy. Though the succession is now secured, magic can't chance the true essence of a person.&lt;/p&gt; &lt;/div&gt;&lt;hr&gt;&lt;h3&gt;&lt;a href="https://www.scribblehub.com/read/1668514-the-realm-needs-a-prince/chapter/1750711/"&gt;&lt;div class="chapter-title"&gt;CHAPTER 1&lt;/div&gt;&lt;/a&gt;&lt;/h3&gt;&lt;div class="chp_raw" id="chp_raw"&gt;&lt;p&gt;The principality of Sorun, a land of meadows at the end of the world, faced perdition. The executioner's blade wasn't in the hand of Sorun's enemies, but the inevitably of time and misfortune. The social fabric of the realm unravelled by itself, as the Sovereign Prince Agand lay on his deathbed without an heir.&lt;/p&gt; &lt;p&gt;Agand had already been old, when the lords had dragged him out of the sacred hermitage to replace his tragically deceased nephew. His marriage to Lady Reisn --a girl young enough to be the prince's daughter-- had been an unwanted duty to both of them. Yet the union had not been entirely without its tender moments of mutual respect and affection.&lt;/p&gt; &lt;p&gt;In a palace of wide towers at the edge of a sea-cliff, the prince prepared for the last rituals of his life, while Reisn neared the end of her pregnancy. Because the forces of death threatened fledgling life, Reisn wouldn't be able to attend her husband in his very last hours.&lt;/p&gt; &lt;p&gt;"I have troubled you overmuch," Agand wheezed. "But I must ask you to take care of the child and realm."&lt;/p&gt; &lt;p&gt;Reisn smiled and clutched the prince's hand. "I will. Goodbye, my husband."&lt;/p&gt; &lt;p&gt;"Goodbye, little Reisn."&lt;/p&gt; &lt;p&gt;The lady kissed Agand on his forehead and left with tears in her eyes. But the death of the prince wasn't what troubled her foremost. Through worry and spellcraft, she had sensed the nature of their child. She would give birth to a girl, not the prince the realm needed.&lt;/p&gt; &lt;p&gt;In preparation, Reisn retreated to her apartments and insisted on solitude with only immaterial servants as her aid.&lt;/p&gt; &lt;p&gt;Blessed with uncharacteristic wisdom, the lords of Sorun would have supported an infant son to the throne. But a princely daughter's hand, the key to rulership, was too tantalising a prize. The ensuing inner struggle was sure to devastate the land.&lt;/p&gt; &lt;p&gt;Though young and unworldly, Lady Reisn knew this. As the childbirth grew imminent, she pondered, what she might do to preserve the realm. So intensely she thought, that the news of Prince Agand's death barely moved her mind, even though she was far from callous.&lt;/p&gt; &lt;p&gt;The realm needed a prince. With her small witchcraft, Reisn called on certain capricious forces. They agreed to give her a son. The infant girl, still unborn, would emerge in the body ready to ripen into a man. But these forces were not unkind, and so they deemed that should the child ever feel himself to be a woman, her body would accommodate.&lt;/p&gt; &lt;p&gt;Lady Reisn agreed and paid the nominal price for her magic: from henceforth her chestnut hair was robbed of its luxurious colour.&lt;/p&gt; &lt;p&gt;After the arduous solitary labour, Reisn was able to hold her son.&lt;/p&gt; &lt;p&gt;In an attempt to alleviate a regret she wasn't quite aware of yet, Reisn named the child Dzain; a name, which had in previous generations adorned headstrong ladies and heedful warriors alike.&lt;/p&gt; &lt;p&gt;With tresses of steely grey, Lady Reisn presented Prince Dzain to the relieved lords of Sorun.&lt;/p&gt; &lt;/div&gt;</description>
