      <description>&lt;div class="wi_fic_desc" property="description"&gt;&lt;p&gt;Eran McGuile never much believed in things like ghosts and guardian angels, relying only on himself for protection all his life. However, after coming into contact with Zacchaeus, the ghost of a man that'd been haunting his apartment for over forty years, Eran has to start reassessing more of his beliefs than he ever thought he would.&lt;/p&gt; &lt;/div&gt;&lt;hr&gt;&lt;h3&gt;&lt;a href="https://www.scribblehub.com/read/1720180-spirit-of-survival/chapter/1720184/"&gt;&lt;div class="chapter-title"&gt;Chapter 1: Sunday, 04:00AM, Mountain Rd. &amp;amp; Main St.&lt;/div&gt;&lt;/a&gt;&lt;/h3&gt;&lt;div class="chp_raw" id="chp_raw"&gt;&lt;p&gt;Eran didn't like to walk alone at night. The fear was instilled deep within him, a fear of the dark evolved from childish anxieties over monsters with rows on rows of teeth to monsters that looked too uncomfortably much just like him. Despite what he might have thought years ago as a foolish teen, Eran knew better by now than to think that fear had outlived its usefulness; that made it all the more important that he walk with his head high, hands shoved into his pockets as he strolled so casually down the lamp-lit streets. From his own experiences, few ever wanted to take their chances on assaulting someone moving with purpose, with a head held high, so this gallant stride was just his first line of defense.&lt;/p&gt; &lt;p&gt;If he had his way, honestly, he wouldn't even be out so late. Everyone outside the bachelorette party had surely been given the wrong idea by his participation in the late-night festivities—most nights, it was a tall order to even pry Eran from the safety of his apartment, but tonight was a special occasion. What compelled him to join the gaggle of giddy young ladies in celebrating his childhood friend's "last night of freedom" was the same force that allowed him to show up dressed in his usual attire of a loose hoodie and pants, or at least so long as the pants were slacks and the garments made some attempt to match in color: a certain someone named Genevive. Ginny had done all she could to make Eran feel nice and welcome, too, with the logic that he'd surely do the same for her if he ever got married.&lt;/p&gt; &lt;p&gt;She was quick to correct herself to the more generous choice of words, amending that stipulation to instead activate &lt;i&gt;when &lt;/i&gt;her dear childhood friend got married. For all Ginny did, bless her heart, there were always going to be little details that she couldn't help in a million years that'd stand out to him.&lt;/p&gt; &lt;p&gt;"Oh, Er, honey, I'm sorry," he recalled her quietly muttering with her hands clasped above her heart, as if she'd mentioned some long-dead loved one of his without thinking. "I really didn't mean to upset you, are you alright?"&lt;/p&gt; &lt;p&gt;He'd screwed his eyes shut tight then, just like he did now.&lt;/p&gt; &lt;p&gt;"Y'just look so lonely," he remembered her slurring later on in the night. "Those bags under your eyes, honey, and that look about ya..."&lt;/p&gt; &lt;p&gt;Eran stopped short in the middle of the road to dig his cigarettes from his pocket.&lt;/p&gt; &lt;p&gt;"Ya look downright haunted," Ginny's voice echoed in his mind.&lt;/p&gt; &lt;p&gt;The hit of that first drag can't come soon enough. With a flick of his lighter, Eran takes a deep pull off of his fresh cigarette, exhaling the smoke in a thick plume after a reflective moment holding all those toxic fumes in his lungs.&lt;/p&gt; &lt;p&gt;That's when another voice chimes in on his thoughts and recollections.&lt;/p&gt; &lt;p&gt;&lt;i&gt;You really oughta quit that, you know.&lt;/i&gt;&lt;/p&gt; &lt;p&gt;&lt;i&gt; &lt;/i&gt;Eran's brows furrow in exhausted recognition. Other than the cacophony of voices ringing out in his mind, he noted the night was otherwise quiet; nothing but the cry of cicadas and chirping of crickets rang out through his immediate surroundings. The brilliant orange skies of the twilight hung above him like a protective shroud; surely he could respond aloud to that unwarranted criticism.&lt;/p&gt; &lt;p&gt;"I didn't think I had memory problems," Eran quipped under his breath before walking again, "but here I am: can't remember asking you a damn thing."&lt;/p&gt; &lt;p&gt;&lt;i&gt;Don't you start that with me, boy, &lt;/i&gt;that voice hissed. &lt;i&gt;It's in my best interest to keep you in good shape, isn't it?&lt;/i&gt;&lt;/p&gt; &lt;p&gt;&lt;i&gt; &lt;/i&gt;"You never quite managed to get me on board with why I should care about your interests."&lt;/p&gt; &lt;p&gt;&lt;i&gt;'Cause my best interests are yours, ain't that obvious?!&lt;/i&gt;&lt;/p&gt; &lt;p&gt;&lt;i&gt; &lt;/i&gt;As Eran's eyes fell shut once more mid-stride, both his voice and the other let out exasperated sighs. Not one moment after, however...&lt;/p&gt; &lt;p&gt;&lt;i&gt;Hey, kid, &lt;/i&gt;the voice suddenly snapped, &lt;i&gt;look alive. &lt;/i&gt;&lt;i&gt;Bogie inbound, 3 o'clock.&lt;/i&gt;&lt;/p&gt; &lt;p&gt;Eran's eyes snapped open just in time to stop himself short of stumbling into a taller man in a disheveled suit. A brief look at the man from head-to-toe clued Eran in that he'd likely just emerged from a similarly wild night to his own, perhaps even more so. The necktie nearly falling off his half-buttoned dress shirt said almost as much as the lipstick stains on his collar and neck, or the glitter embedded from the skin of a shimmering performer into his own. Once the man regained his own balance—clearly a more concentrated effort than it was for Eran, given how the man swayed back and forth so precariously—he managed to pull a goofy grin in some effort to save face.&lt;/p&gt; &lt;p&gt;"Real sorry, uh..." The businessman's hazy eyes squinted briefly at the wiry hairs sprouting from Eran's chin and upper lip, "sir, I, uh..."&lt;/p&gt; &lt;p&gt;"Don't gotta explain shit to me," Eran insisted, raising a hand to cut the other off. "I get it. It's Friday night, just have a good one."&lt;/p&gt; &lt;p&gt;"Hahah, hell &lt;i&gt;yeah &lt;/i&gt;it's Friday night! &lt;i&gt;Woo!&lt;/i&gt;"&lt;/p&gt; &lt;p&gt;That pump of the man's fist nearly pulls the ratty suit coat right off his other arm as it's left to dangle, inevitably causing the man to stumble around for another second or two. Watching his bumbling charade, Eran really had to wonder if his health was really something to be concerned over.&lt;/p&gt; &lt;p&gt;&lt;i&gt;Of course it is,&lt;/i&gt; the voice reliably chimes in. &lt;i&gt;So you don't end up like THAT, got it?&lt;/i&gt;&lt;/p&gt; &lt;p&gt;&lt;i&gt; &lt;/i&gt;"Hah..." Naturally, being thrown off-balance wasn't going to stop this buffoon's laughter, but some errant thought still succeeds in letting those messy howls taper out. Judging from how those bloodshot, glassy eyes looked Eran over none-too-subtly in return, a sinking feeling in the lad's gut told him he had two reasonable guesses for what that thought could have been.&lt;/p&gt; &lt;p&gt;"Y'know," the man drawled, "I coulda sworn the gay bar was on the &lt;i&gt;other &lt;/i&gt;side of the street."&lt;/p&gt; &lt;p&gt;"Excuse me?"&lt;/p&gt; &lt;p&gt;Eran's hands balled into fists on instinct. He knew the distinct tone of fighting words by heart, his muscle memory attuned to its sound like a machine. Just as the thought crossed his mind to raise those fists, however, even if the entire process took perhaps a fraction of a second, that voice spoke up again:&lt;/p&gt; &lt;p&gt;&lt;i&gt;Kid, wait! He's got ya outclassed!&lt;/i&gt;&lt;/p&gt; &lt;p&gt;&lt;i&gt; &lt;/i&gt;What the hell did this guy think he was doing? Eran's body stops short, instead leaving him to grind his teeth and let out a subtle growl. As the drunken man shambled closer, Eran could feel the stress clamp around his head as the smell of cheap whiskey assaulted his senses.&lt;/p&gt; &lt;p&gt;"Just sayin'," the man continued on, chuckling to himself again, "you seem like you'd be popular down there. I'm not gay or nothin', but has anybody told ya you've got beautiful eyes, man?"&lt;/p&gt; &lt;p&gt;How the hell could this loser outclass him?&lt;/p&gt; &lt;p&gt;&lt;i&gt;Gotcha beat on height, &lt;/i&gt;the voice clarified. &lt;i&gt;Even if he's drunk, all he'd have to do is fall on you, you couldn't push his dead weight off ya.&lt;/i&gt;&lt;i&gt; Beanpole or not, a boy that long's gonna be heavy when he's nearly dead-drunk.&lt;/i&gt;&lt;/p&gt; &lt;p&gt;&lt;i&gt; &lt;/i&gt;"Not to mention those hips, that little waist..."&lt;/p&gt; &lt;p&gt;&lt;i&gt;But I'm not saying "don't fight". No, this asshole needs to be taught a lesson.&lt;/i&gt;&lt;/p&gt; &lt;p&gt;&lt;i&gt; &lt;/i&gt;Eran took another step back, if only to buy himself a little more time and silently ask just what the hell his passenger was suggesting. Similar to the first, another step back didn't stop the lecherous stranger from closing the distance again.&lt;/p&gt; &lt;p&gt;&lt;i&gt;I'm saying "let me help", &lt;/i&gt;the voice finally answered. &lt;i&gt;A height advantage won't matter if he's outnumbered, and I can do it. Let me try, at least?&lt;/i&gt;&lt;/p&gt; &lt;p&gt;&lt;i&gt; &lt;/i&gt;Eran craned his head back, still scowling up at the man leering and giggling down at him.&lt;/p&gt; &lt;p&gt;"And those pretty lil' lips..."&lt;/p&gt; &lt;p&gt;His little partner could do whatever the hell he wanted, really, if he wasn't going to stand in Eran's way.&lt;/p&gt; &lt;p&gt;"I really ain't gay, but I wouldn't mind seein' &lt;i&gt;you &lt;/i&gt;on your knees if I had to fuck any fag—"&lt;/p&gt; &lt;p&gt;His body moved before he could even think to move it. Another step back set Eran's right foot in position to hold his weight, his left pivoting along with his torso to cut off that salacious ramble with a firm left hook to the chin. His guard didn't drop for even a moment, nor did he relent in his opening, following a hook with an uppercut, another hook from the right; the name of his game was always to overwhelm while his opponent was under-prepared.&lt;/p&gt; &lt;p&gt;As Eran hopped back to catch his breath, however, something clicked in his mind.&lt;/p&gt; &lt;p&gt;Usually, even the most uselessly intoxicated freaks would try to fight back, whether fueled by blind hatred or sheer entitlement. But this time, &lt;i&gt;this &lt;/i&gt;guy? He hadn't even tried. In fact, as Eran wiped the sweat from his brow, he could finally see how the other man seemed to dangle before him; arms raised at right angles, shoulders shrugged, as if he were a mere puppet held aloft by invisible strings. For a moment, Eran could only stare in confusion.&lt;/p&gt; &lt;p&gt;A sudden impact to the stranger's back coaxed a pained grunt from its target and answered Eran's confusion all at once.&lt;/p&gt; &lt;p&gt;&lt;i&gt;What's the matter, Rocky?&lt;/i&gt;&lt;/p&gt; &lt;p&gt;&lt;i&gt; &lt;/i&gt;The familiar weathered voice of Eran's little spiritual partner snickered, already far too pleased with himself.&lt;/p&gt; &lt;p&gt;&lt;i&gt;Don't tell me you got all your licks in just then, he's still conscious. And I don't know how long he's gonna be still, either, so you better hurry up.&lt;/i&gt;&lt;/p&gt; &lt;p&gt;&lt;i&gt; &lt;/i&gt;He should have guessed this was what "help" looked like. Though he still sighed, this time, Eran wasn't able to stop himself from grinning a little, himself.&lt;/p&gt; &lt;p&gt;"I don't think this is an honorable fight anymore, then," Eran joked, still happy to follow up a metaphysical knee to his opponent's spine with a more tangible fist to his gut.&lt;/p&gt; &lt;p&gt;&lt;i&gt;Oh yeah, and this guy was the picture of honor. What a damn shame.&lt;/i&gt;&lt;/p&gt; &lt;p&gt;&lt;i&gt; &lt;/i&gt;"W-Who the &lt;i&gt;fuck&lt;/i&gt;...?"&lt;/p&gt; &lt;p&gt;It was almost impressive that this guy still had any wind to wonder that out loud after a breathtaking assault from both sides. All that considered, however, it probably wasn't going to be a good idea to leave him conscious for long enough to &lt;i&gt;keep &lt;/i&gt;wondering. Watching the other rise by his arms with a sudden upwards jerk, Eran raised his fists and squared his stance once more...&lt;/p&gt; &lt;p&gt;Before motioning upwards with quick waves of his hand.&lt;/p&gt; &lt;p&gt;"Raise him up a lil' higher, Zac."&lt;/p&gt; &lt;p&gt;He didn't have to see his partner's face to feel the roll of his eyes, yet still Eran's hapless assailant rose higher in the empty night skies. Eran shook his head, repeating the motion as his grin grew.&lt;/p&gt; &lt;p&gt;"Higher," he demanded, "I wanna beat my vertical record."&lt;/p&gt; &lt;p&gt;&lt;i&gt;You and your damn pride, kid...&lt;/i&gt;&lt;/p&gt; &lt;p&gt;Even so, the man is raised even higher, and Eran draws in a sharp breath through his bared teeth.&lt;/p&gt; &lt;p&gt;"Perfect."&lt;/p&gt; &lt;p&gt;On that night, at that time, on the corner of Mountain and Main, Eran McGuile broke his previous vertical jump height record of 18 inches with a magnificent 20-inch leap to deliver the most cathartic kick to a man's groin of his life. Only when he was certain the stranger had passed out, either from inebriation or pain, did he ask for Zacchaeus to finally drop him; only when the both of them were certain they could still see the man breathing, however shallow, did Eran feel satisfied enough to continue his confident stride down the empty road.&lt;/p&gt; &lt;p&gt;"I really hope we didn't just leave a man for dead," he still caught himself mumbling.&lt;/p&gt; &lt;p&gt;&lt;i&gt;He'll be fine, &lt;/i&gt;Zac assured him, though not without a noticeable hint of mischief in his snickering voice. &lt;i&gt;The hospital's just on the other side of the street.&lt;/i&gt;&lt;/p&gt; &lt;p&gt;&lt;i&gt; &lt;/i&gt;Oh, if only he could tell Ginny that being haunted wasn't actually all that bad.&lt;/p&gt; &lt;/div&gt;</description>
