      <description>&lt;div class="wi_fic_desc" property="description"&gt;&lt;p&gt;The Christ’s Dawn Class of 2003 Welcomes You To Their Twenty Year Reunion!&lt;/p&gt; &lt;p&gt;Sean’s had a rough twenty years, his best friend disappeared right after high school, and nothing in his life since has gone how he’d planned. Instead of designing aircraft, he builds them, one rivet at a time, and instead of a wife and kids and a big full life, he’s perpetually lonely.&lt;/p&gt; &lt;p&gt;Beth on the other hand, hadn’t been home in twenty years, and when she left, she’d still been pretending to be a boy. By many measures of success she was better off, good career in the field she’d intended to be in, friends and found family who care for her. But coming out had cost her dearly, her parents had disowned her, so she’d decided to make a clean break from her old life.&lt;/p&gt; &lt;p&gt;Both of them are stuck — until their class reunion brings them back together, and Beth makes Sean an offer.&lt;/p&gt; &lt;/div&gt;&lt;hr&gt;&lt;h3&gt;&lt;a href="https://www.scribblehub.com/read/1673892-little-blue-pill/chapter/1703742/"&gt;&lt;div class="chapter-title"&gt;Prologue: Graduation&lt;/div&gt;&lt;/a&gt;&lt;/h3&gt;&lt;div class="chp_raw" id="chp_raw"&gt;&lt;h3&gt;&lt;strong&gt;May 22, 2003 — Thursday&lt;/strong&gt;&lt;/h3&gt; &lt;p&gt;Sean sighed, it had already been an &lt;em&gt;hour&lt;/em&gt; since the &lt;em&gt;three-hour&lt;/em&gt; ceremony that was supposed to end his high school torment at Christ’s Dawn, but then there was the socializing after the ceremony. The lobby of the church they rented for the ceremony was overcrowded and loud, and Sean was just about out of patience. The only good to come out of all this was he had a full ride scholarship to the local university. He’d been obsessed with the idea of designing aircraft since kindergarten, and couldn’t wait to finally start working on something &lt;em&gt;real.&lt;/em&gt;&lt;/p&gt; &lt;p&gt;He wouldn’t have even been here tonight if the school hadn’t said that if you didn’t attend, you didn’t get your diploma, so everyone was here — with the notable exception of Jenny. She hadn’t been to school in person since February, when it was realized that she’d gotten &lt;em&gt;pregnant.&lt;/em&gt; It had hardly been surprising to the students, they all &lt;em&gt;knew&lt;/em&gt; she’d been dating that basketball player and snuck out of her hotel room after a road game to have sex with him. The school didn’t even teach ‘abstinence only’, preferring to let the kid’s churches push purity rings and washed their hands of it.&lt;/p&gt; &lt;p&gt;He’d been looking for his small group of friends since the ceremony ended, but Blake got back with his extremely on-again-off-again girlfriend since the end of classes. He was off somewhere with her on the other side of the room with her, probably trying to play the good boyfriend around her family. Sean suspected Nathan slipped out quietly early — he could see what should’ve been his table, but it was empty. Josh, though, should be &lt;em&gt;somewhere&lt;/em&gt; nearby, and he’d disappeared.&lt;/p&gt; &lt;p&gt;“Sean!” Sean heard Josh’s familiar voice call across the too crowded, noisy lobby, and he turned to look, grinning as he did.&lt;/p&gt; &lt;p&gt;“Josh,” Sean said, as soon as Josh got close enough, they could talk without shouting over the din. “There you are!”&lt;/p&gt; &lt;p&gt;“We made it!” Josh said excitedly. “Holy shit, we made it, Sean! Sorry for disappearing, had to find a toilet something fierce.”&lt;/p&gt; &lt;p&gt;“Language,” a teacher nearby chided — one of the science teachers who was a real stickler for the rules, and who moonlighted as one of the bible teachers.&lt;/p&gt; &lt;p&gt;“I’m a graduate, now,” Josh said and stuck his chin in the air, but thankfully the teacher got distracted from doing anything about it. What he could’ve done, Sean didn’t know, but better to not find out.&lt;/p&gt; &lt;p&gt;“Heck yeah, we are,” Sean said. “So, California, right?”&lt;/p&gt; &lt;p&gt;“Yup,” Josh said. “I’m going to learn to program the rockets that you learn to design.”&lt;/p&gt; &lt;p&gt;“Hah,” Sean laughed. “That’s the dream.”&lt;/p&gt; &lt;p&gt;It had been a recurring discussion of theirs, but they both knew it was a bit of a fantasy drawn from too many sci-fi books. Realistically, Sean would be just another cog at one of the local aircraft companies, one of any number of engineers working on designing a small part of a large aircraft. His scholarship to Wichita State would cover his degree in Aerospace Engineering — but the school was far more interested in the aero aspect than the space part. At least it was what his family could afford with the scholarship, and it would secure him a good job he could support himself on.&lt;/p&gt; &lt;p&gt;&lt;em&gt;“Josh!”&lt;/em&gt; he heard Josh’s mom call sharply. “It’s time to go, we’ve got to get to the party, the family are all at the restaurant waiting.”&lt;/p&gt; &lt;p&gt;“Ugh,” Josh said. “Sorry Sean, gotta run — sorry the parents insisted on the party for just me.”&lt;/p&gt; &lt;p&gt;“It’s fine,” Sean said. “Last Thursday was &lt;em&gt;our&lt;/em&gt; party.”&lt;/p&gt; &lt;p&gt;“That movie was so great,” Josh said. “I’m so glad you invited me! Parents still don’t know what movie I went to.”&lt;/p&gt; &lt;p&gt;“Probably for the best,” Sean said. “I’ll send a message when I get back from working summer camp, we can hang out before you have to move out there.”&lt;/p&gt; &lt;p&gt;“Sure,” Josh said, glancing at his mother, who looked increasingly impatient. “And I’ll email you from school once I get there, with fewer eyes over my shoulder. Got to run, talk to you later, Sean, going to miss you.”&lt;/p&gt; &lt;p&gt;“Will miss you too,” Sean said as Josh turned to leave. “See you in a couple of months!”&lt;/p&gt; &lt;p&gt;“Hey hon,” Sean’s mom said, coming up beside him as Josh left with his parents looking back like he was sad to go, his mom looking upset at him. “Now that you got to say bye to Josh, you ready to go to the restaurant?”&lt;/p&gt; &lt;p&gt;“Yeah,” Sean said, his annoyance at Josh’s parents and this whole evening deepening. “I… might be a bit — want to blow off some steam.”&lt;/p&gt; &lt;p&gt;“Sure,” his dad said. “There’s probably going to be a wait at the restaurant anyway.” His parents were used to him ‘blowing off some steam’ and knew he drove his truck the long way around to wherever he was going, likely too fast, and definitely with the music too loud.&lt;/p&gt; &lt;p&gt;He helped them carry the stuff from his table detailing his accomplishments from the last four years out to their car, before finding his nearly as old as him S-10 pickup in the parking lot. Sean paused after turning his truck on and reached into the glove compartment, pulling out a CD he’d made especially for tonight. He rolled down the driver side window manually as he inserted it into the aftermarket stereo, and turned the volume up slowly. The speakers he’d spent his precious summer job money on ramping up to nuisance levels. The long, distinct intro of &lt;em&gt;Enter Sandman&lt;/em&gt; started playing as others around him turned to look his way.&lt;/p&gt; &lt;p&gt;Four years ago, he’d signed a pledge saying he wouldn’t listen to rock music, watch R rated films that weren’t historical, or generally be ‘amoral’. His parents hadn’t held him to it, but he’d been careful around school grounds — he didn’t want trouble. He saw his former english teacher look his way and shake her head and the asshole appeared to say &lt;em&gt;something,&lt;/em&gt; but Sean couldn’t hear whatever patronizing, disapproving drivel had spilled from her mouth as the music ramped up. He was &lt;em&gt;free&lt;/em&gt; at last of the school’s bullshit rules, and he didn’t care anymore.&lt;/p&gt; &lt;p&gt;Sean gunned the engine in neutral and then pulled out of his space somewhat carefully, turning to stick his tongue out at the disapproving looks of the people around him. His scholarship was secured, and in two weeks, he’d be at the camp he worked at in the summer, cleansing himself of the stress of his senior year. He’d get a degree from a top-rated program, and not have had to pay for classes, books, and he’d be living at home to save room and board. By the time he got to the restaurant, he was sure that his life was looking up, with nothing but good things in the future.&lt;/p&gt; &lt;/div&gt;</description>
